# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cotton-gin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The **Ajanta Caves** are 30 rock-cut Buddhist cave monuments dating from the second century BCE to about 480 CE in Aurangabad district of Maharashtra state in India.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Ajanta Caves are a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Universally regarded as masterpieces of Buddhist religious art, the caves include paintings and rock-cut sculptures, described as among the finest surviving examples of ancient Indian art, particularly expressive paintings that present emotions through gesture, pose and form.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The caves were built in two phases, the first starting around the second century BCE and the second occurring from 400 to 650 CE, according to older accounts, or in a brief period of 460–480 CE according to later scholarship.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta Caves constitute ancient monasteries (*Viharas*) and worship-halls (*Chaityas*) of different Buddhist traditions carved into a 75-metre (246 ft) wall of rock.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The caves also present paintings depicting the past lives and rebirths of the Buddha, pictorial tales from *Aryasura's Jatakamala*, and rock-cut sculptures of Buddhist deities.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Textual records suggest that these caves served as a monsoon retreat for monks, as well as a resting site for merchants and pilgrims in ancient India.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] While vivid colours and mural wall paintings were abundant in Indian history as evidenced by historical records, Caves 1, 2, 16 and 17 of Ajanta form the largest corpus of surviving ancient Indian wall-paintings.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta Caves are mentioned in the memoirs of several medieval-era Chinese Buddhist travelers.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] They were covered by the jungle until accidentally "discovered" and brought to contemporary attention in 1819 by Colonel John Smith during a tiger-hunting expedition on a tiger-hunting party.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The caves are located in the rocky northern wall of the U-shaped gorge of the River Waghur, in the Deccan Plateau.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Within the gorge are a number of waterfalls, audible from outside the caves when the river is high.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Ajanta is one of the major tourist attractions of Maharashtra.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] It is about 59 kilometres (37 miles) from the city of Jalgaon, Maharashtra, India, 104 kilometres (65 miles) from the city of Aurangabad, and 350 kilometres (220 miles) east-northeast of Mumbai.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] There are Ellora Caves another UNESCO World Heritage Site, which is 100 Kilometres (62 miles) contains Hindu, Jain, and Buddhist caves, the last dating from a period similar to Ajanta.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta style is also found in the Ellora Caves and other near about caves such as the Elephanta Caves, Aurangabad Caves, Shivleni Caves and the cave temples of Karnataka.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Nearest airports are Jalgaon and Sambhaji Nagar, followed by Mumbai, and nearest railway stations are Jalgaon and Bhusawal.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta Caves are generally agreed to have been made in two distinct phases; first during the 2nd century BCE to 1st century CE, and second several centuries later.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The caves consist of 36 identifiable foundations, some of them discovered after the original numbering of the caves from 1 through 29.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The later-identified caves have been suffixed with the letters of the alphabet, such as 15A, identified between originally numbered caves 15 and 16.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave numbering is a convention of convenience and does not reflect the chronological order of their construction.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The earliest group consists of caves 9, 10, 12, 13 and 15 A.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The murals in these caves depict stories from the Jatakas.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Later caves reflect the artistic influence of the Gupta period, but there are differing opinions on which century in which the early caves were built.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Walter Spink, they were made during the period 100 BCE to 100 CE, probably under the patronage of the Satavahana dynasty (230 BCE – 220 CE) who ruled the region.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Other datings prefer the period of the Maurya Empire (300 BCE to 100 BCE).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Of these, caves 9 and 10 are stupa containing worship halls of *chaitya-griha* form, and caves 12, 13, and 15A are *vihāras* (see the architecture section below for descriptions of these types).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The first Satavahana period caves lacked figurative sculpture, emphasizing the stupa instead.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink, once the Satavahana period caves were made, the site was not further developed for a considerable period until the mid-5th century.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] However, the early caves were in use during this dormant period, and Buddhist pilgrims visited the site, according to the records left by Chinese pilgrim Faxian around 400 CE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The second phase of construction at the Ajanta Caves site began in the 5th century.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] For a long time it was thought that the later caves were made over an extended period from the 4th to the 7th centuries CE, but in recent decades a series of studies by the leading expert on the caves, Walter M.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Spink, have argued that most of the work took place over the very brief period from 460 to 480 CE, during the reign of Hindu Emperor Harishena of the Vākāṭaka dynasty.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This view has been criticised by some scholars, but is now broadly accepted by most authors of general books on Indian art, for example, Huntington and Harle.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The second phase is attributed to the theistic Mahāyāna, or Greater Vehicle tradition of Buddhism.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Caves of the second period are 1–8, 11, 14–29, some possibly extensions of earlier caves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Caves 19, 26, and 29 are *chaitya-grihas*, the rest *viharas*.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The most elaborate caves were produced in this period, which included some refurbishing and repainting of the early caves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Spink states that it is possible to establish dating for this period with a very high level of precision; a fuller account of his chronology is given below.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Although debate continues, Spink's ideas are increasingly widely accepted, at least in their broad conclusions.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The Archaeological Survey of India website still presents the traditional dating: "The second phase of paintings started around 5th–6th centuries A.D. and continued for the next two centuries".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink, the construction activity at the incomplete Ajanta Caves was abandoned by wealthy patrons in about 480 CE, a few years after the death of Harishena.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] However, states Spink, the caves appear to have been in use for a period of time as evidenced by the wear of the pivot holes in caves constructed close to 480 CE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The second phase of constructions and decorations at Ajanta corresponds to the very apogee of Classical India, or India's golden age.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] However, at that time, the Gupta Empire was already weakening from internal political issues and from the assaults of the Hūṇas, so that the Vakatakas were actually one of the most powerful empires in India.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Some of the Hūṇas, the Alchon Huns of Toramana, were precisely ruling the neighbouring area of Malwa, at the doorstep of the Western Deccan, at the time the Ajanta Caves were made.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Richard Cohen, a description of the caves by 7th-century Chinese Traveller Xuanzang and scattered medieval graffiti suggest that the Ajanta Caves were known and probably in use subsequently, but without a stable or steady Buddhist community presence.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta caves are mentioned in the 17th-century text *Ain-i-Akbari* by Abu al-Fazl, as twenty four rock-cut cave temples each with remarkable idols.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] On 28 April 1819 a British officer named John Smith, of the 28th Cavalry, while hunting tigers was shown the entrance to Cave No.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] 10 when a local shepherd boy guided him to the location and the door.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The caves were well known by locals already.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Captain Smith went to a nearby village and asked the villagers to come to the site with axes, spears, torches, and drums, to cut down the tangled jungle growth that made entering the cave difficult.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] He first saw ceilings with beautiful and artistically drawn faces on them, then he noticed monastic halls which helped him identify their Buddhist origin.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] He then deliberately damaged an image on the wall by scratching his name and the date over the painting of a bodhisattva.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Since he stood on a five-foot high pile of rubble collected over the years, the inscription is well above the eye-level gaze of an adult today.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] A paper on the caves by William Erskine was read to the Bombay Literary Society in 1822.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Within a few decades, the caves became famous for their exotic setting, impressive architecture, and above all their exceptional and unique paintings.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] A number of large projects to copy the paintings were made in the century after rediscovery.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] In 1848, the Royal Asiatic Society established the "Bombay Cave Temple Commission" to clear, tidy and record the most important rock-cut sites in the Bombay Presidency, with John Wilson as president.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] In 1861 this became the nucleus of the new Archaeological Survey of India.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] During the colonial era, the Ajanta site was in the territory of the princely state of the Hyderabad and not British India.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] In the early 1920s, Mir Osman Ali Khan, the last Nizam of Hyderabad, appointed people to restore the artwork, converted the site into a museum and built a road to bring tourists to the site for a fee.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] These efforts resulted in early mismanagement, states Richard Cohen, and hastened the deterioration of the site.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Post-independence, the state government of Maharashtra built arrival, transport, facilities, and better site management.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The modern Visitor Center has good parking facilities and public conveniences and ASI operated buses run at regular intervals from Visitor Center to the caves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The Nizam's Director of Archaeology obtained the services of two experts from Italy, Professor Lorenzo Cecconi, assisted by Count Orsini, to restore the paintings in the caves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Despite these efforts, later neglect led to the paintings degrading in quality once again.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Since 1983, Ajanta caves have been listed among the UNESCO World Heritage Sites of India.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta Caves, along with the Ellora Caves, have become the most popular tourist destination in Maharashtra, and are often crowded at holiday times, increasing the threat to the caves, especially the paintings.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The caves are carved out of flood basalt and granite rock of a cliff, part of the Deccan Traps formed by successive volcanic eruptions at the end of the Cretaceous geological period.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The rock is layered horizontally, and somewhat variable in quality.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This variation within the rock layers required the artists to amend their carving methods and plans in places.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The inhomogeneity in the rock has also led to cracks and collapses in the centuries that followed, as with the lost portico to cave 1.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Excavation began by cutting a narrow tunnel at roof level, which was expanded downwards and outwards; as evidenced by some of the incomplete caves such as the partially-built *vihara* caves 21 through 24 and the abandoned incomplete cave 28.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The sculpture artists likely worked at both excavating the rocks and making the intricate carvings of pillars, roof, and idols; further, the sculpture and painting work inside a cave were integrated parallel tasks.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] A grand gateway to the site was carved, at the apex of the gorge's horseshoe between caves 15 and 16, as approached from the river, and it is decorated with elephants on either side and a nāga, or protective Naga (snake) deity.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Similar methods and application of artist talent is observed in other cave temples of India, such as those from Hinduism and Jainism.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] These include the Ellora Caves, Ghatotkacha Caves, Elephanta Caves, Bagh Caves, Badami Caves, Aurangabad Caves and Shivleni Caves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The caves from the first period seem to have been paid for by a number of different patrons to gain merit, with several inscriptions recording the donation of particular portions of a single cave.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The later caves were each commissioned as a complete unit by a single patron from the local rulers or their court elites, again for merit in Buddhist afterlife beliefs as evidenced by inscriptions such as those in Cave 17.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The majority of the caves are *vihara* halls with symmetrical square plans.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] To each vihara hall are attached smaller square dormitory cells cut into the walls.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This change reflects the shift from Hinayana to Mahāyāna Buddhism.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] These caves are often called monasteries.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The central square space of the interior of the viharas is defined by square columns forming a more-or-less square open area.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Outside this are long rectangular aisles on each side, forming a kind of cloister.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Along the side and rear walls are a number of small cells entered by a narrow doorway; these are roughly square, and have small niches on their back walls.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The centre of the rear wall has a larger shrine-room behind, containing a large Buddha statue.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The viharas of the earlier period are much simpler, and lack shrines.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Spink places the change to a design with a shrine to the middle of the second period, with many caves being adapted to add a shrine in mid-excavation, or after the original phase.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The plan of Cave 1 shows one of the largest viharas, but is fairly typical of the later group.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Many others, such as Cave 16, lack the vestibule to the shrine, which leads straight off the main hall.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 6 is two viharas, one above the other, connected by internal stairs, with sanctuaries on both levels.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Top: Interior of Ajanta chaitya hall, Cave 26, photo by Robert Gill (c.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] 1868); Bottom: James Fergusson sketch of Cave 19 worship hall.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The other type of main hall architecture is the narrower rectangular plan with high arched ceiling type *chaitya-griha* – literally, "the house of stupa".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This hall is longitudinally divided into a nave and two narrower side aisles separated by a symmetrical row of pillars, with a stupa in the apse.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The stupa is surrounded by pillars and concentric walking space for circumambulation.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Some of the caves have elaborate carved entrances, some with large windows over the door to admit light.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] There is often a colonnaded porch or verandah, with another space inside the doors running the width of the cave.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The oldest worship halls at Ajanta were built in the 2nd to 1st century BCE, the newest ones in the late 5th century CE, and the architecture of both resembles the architecture of a Christian church, but without the crossing or chapel chevette.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta Caves follow the Cathedral-style architecture found in still older rock-cut cave carvings of ancient India, such as the Lomas Rishi Cave of the Ajivikas near Gaya in Bihar dated to the 3rd century BCE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] These chaitya-griha are called worship or prayer halls.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The four completed *chaitya* halls are caves 9 and 10 from the early period, and caves 19 and 26 from the later period of construction.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] All follow the typical form found elsewhere, with high ceilings and a central "nave" leading to the stupa, which is near the back, but allows walking behind it, as walking around stupas was (and remains) a common element of Buddhist worship (*pradakshina*).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The later two have high ribbed roofs carved into the rock, which reflect timber forms, and the earlier two are thought to have used actual timber ribs and are now smooth, the original wood presumed to have perished.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The two later halls have a rather unusual arrangement (also found in Cave 10 at Ellora) where the stupa is fronted by a large relief sculpture of the Buddha, standing in Cave 19 and seated in Cave 26.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 29 is a late and very incomplete *chaitya* hall.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The form of columns in the work of the first period is very plain and un-embellished, with both *chaitya* halls using simple octagonal columns, which were later painted with images of the Buddha, people and monks in robes.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] In the second period columns were far more varied and inventive, often changing profile over their height, and with elaborate carved capitals, often spreading wide.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Many columns are carved over all their surface with floral motifs and Mahayana deities, some fluted and others carved with decoration all over, as in cave 1.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Most of the Ajanta caves, and almost all the murals paintings date from nearly 600 years later, during a second phase of construction.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The paintings in the Ajanta caves predominantly narrate the Jataka tales.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] These are Buddhist legends describing the previous births of the Buddha.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] These fables embed ancient morals and cultural lores that are also found in the fables and legends of Hindu and Jain texts.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The Jataka tales are exemplified through the life example and sacrifices that the Buddha made in hundreds of his past incarnations, where he is depicted as having been reborn as an animal or human.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Mural paintings survive from both the earlier and later groups of caves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Some connections with the art of Gandhara can also be noted, and there is evidence of a shared artistic idiom.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Four of the later caves have large and relatively well-preserved mural paintings which, states James Harle, "have come to represent Indian mural painting to the non-specialist", and represent "the great glories not only of Gupta but of all Indian art".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] They fall into two stylistic groups, with the most famous in Caves 16 and 17, and apparently later paintings in Caves 1 and 2.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The latter group were thought to be a century or later than the others, but the revised chronology proposed by Spink would place them in the 5th century as well, perhaps contemporary with it in a more progressive style, or one reflecting a team from a different region.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta frescos are classical paintings and the work of confident artists, without cliches, rich and full.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] They are luxurious, sensuous and celebrate physical beauty, aspects that early Western observers felt were shockingly out of place in these caves presumed to be meant for religious worship and ascetic monastic life.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The paintings are in "dry fresco", painted on top of a dry plaster surface rather than into wet plaster.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] All the paintings appear to be the work of painters supported by discriminating connoisseurship and sophisticated patrons from an urban atmosphere.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] It is known from literary sources that painting was widely practised and appreciated in the Gupta period.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Unlike much Indian mural painting, compositions are not laid out in horizontal bands like a frieze, but show large scenes spreading in all directions from a single figure or group at the centre.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The ceilings are also painted with sophisticated and elaborate decorative motifs, many derived from sculpture.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The paintings in cave 1, which according to Spink was commissioned by Harisena himself, concentrate on those Jataka tales which show previous lives of the Buddha as a king, rather than as deer or elephant or another Jataka animal.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The scenes depict the Buddha as about to renounce the royal life.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] In general the later caves seem to have been painted on finished areas as excavating work continued elsewhere in the cave, as shown in caves 2 and 16 in particular.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink's account of the chronology of the caves, the abandonment of work in 478 after a brief busy period accounts for the absence of painting in places including cave 4 and the shrine of cave 17, the later being plastered in preparation for paintings that were never done.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Walter Spink has over recent decades developed a very precise and circumstantial chronology for the second period of work on the site, which unlike earlier scholars, he places entirely in the 5th century.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This is based on evidence such as the inscriptions and artistic style, dating of nearby cave temple sites, comparative chronology of the dynasties, combined with the many uncompleted elements of the caves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] He believes the earlier group of caves, which like other scholars he dates only approximately, to the period "between 100 BCE – 100 CE", were at some later point completely abandoned and remained so "for over three centuries".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This changed during the Hindu emperor Harishena of the Vakataka Dynasty, who reigned from 460 to his death in 477, who sponsored numerous new caves during his reign.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Harisena's rule extended the Central Indian Vakataka Empire to include a stretch of the east coast of India; the Gupta Empire ruled northern India at the same period, and the Pallava dynasty much of the south.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink, Harishena encouraged a group of associates, including his prime minister Varahadeva and Upendragupta, the sub-king in whose territory Ajanta was, to dig out new caves, which were individually commissioned, some containing inscriptions recording the donation.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This activity began in many caves simultaneously about 462.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This activity was mostly suspended in 468 because of threats from the neighbouring Asmaka kings.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Thereafter work continued on only Caves 1, Harisena's own commission, and 17–20, commissioned by Upendragupta.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] In 472 the situation was such that work was suspended completely, in a period that Spink calls "the Hiatus", which lasted until about 475, by which time the Asmakas had replaced Upendragupta as the local rulers.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Work was then resumed, but again disrupted by Harisena's death in 477, soon after which major excavation ceased, except at cave 26, which the Asmakas were sponsoring themselves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The Asmakas launched a revolt against Harisena's son, which brought about the end of the Vakataka Dynasty.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] In the years 478–480 CE major excavation by important patrons was replaced by a rash of "intrusions" – statues added to existing caves, and small shrines dotted about where there was space between them.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] These were commissioned by less powerful individuals, some monks, who had not previously been able to make additions to the large excavations of the rulers and courtiers.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] They were added to the facades, the return sides of the entrances, and to walls inside the caves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink, "After 480, not a single image was ever made again at the site".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] However, there exists a Rashtrakuta inscription outside of cave 26 dateable to end of seventh or early 8th century, suggesting the caves were not abandoned until then.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Spink does not use "circa" in his dates, but says that "one should allow a margin of error of one year or perhaps even two in all cases".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta Caves were built in a period when both the Buddha and the Hindu gods were simultaneously revered in Indian culture.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink and other scholars, the royal Vakataka sponsors of the Ajanta Caves probably worshipped both Hindu and Buddhist gods.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This is evidenced by inscriptions in which these rulers, who are otherwise known as Hindu devotees, made Buddhist dedications to the caves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] A terracotta plaque of Mahishasuramardini, also known as Durga, was also found in a burnt-brick vihara monastery facing the caves on the right bank of the river Waghora that has been recently excavated.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This suggest that the deity was possibly under worship by the artisans.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Yuko Yokoschi and Walter Spink, the excavated artifacts of the 5th century near the site suggest that the Ajanta caves deployed a huge number of builders.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 1 was built on the eastern end of the horseshoe-shaped scarp and is now the first cave the visitor encounters.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This cave, when first made, would have been in a less prominent position, right at the end of the row.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink, it is one of the last caves to have been excavated, when the best sites had been taken, and was never fully inaugurated for worship by the dedication of the Buddha image in the central shrine.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This is shown by the absence of sooty deposits from butter lamps on the base of the shrine image, and the lack of damage to the paintings that would have happened if the garland-hooks around the shrine had been in use for any period of time.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Spink states that the Vākāṭaka Emperor Harishena was the benefactor of the work, and this is reflected in the emphasis on imagery of royalty in the cave, with those Jataka tales being selected that tell of those previous lives of the Buddha in which he was royal.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cliff has a steeper slope here than at other caves, so to achieve a tall grand facade it was necessary to cut far back into the slope, giving a large courtyard in front of the facade.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] There was originally a columned portico in front of the present facade, which can be seen "half-intact in the 1880s" in pictures of the site, but this fell down completely and the remains, despite containing fine carvings, were carelessly thrown down the slope into the river and lost.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This cave (35.7 m × 27.6 m) has one of the most elaborate carved facades, with relief sculptures on entablature and ridges, and most surfaces embellished with decorative carving.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] There are scenes carved from the life of the Buddha as well as a number of decorative motifs.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] A two-pillared portico, visible in the 19th-century photographs, has since perished.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave has a forecourt with cells fronted by pillared vestibules on either side.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave has a porch with simple cells at both ends.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The absence of pillared vestibules on the ends suggests that the porch was not excavated in the latest phase of Ajanta when pillared vestibules had become customary.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Most areas of the porch were once covered with murals, of which many fragments remain, especially on the ceiling.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] There are three doorways: a central doorway and two side doorways.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Two square windows were carved between the doorways to brighten the interiors.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Each wall of the hall inside is nearly 40 feet (12 m) long and 20 feet (6.1 m) high.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Twelve pillars make a square colonnade inside, supporting the ceiling and creating spacious aisles along the walls.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] There is a shrine carved on the rear wall to house an impressive seated image of the Buddha, his hands being in the ***Dhammacakkappavattana** mudra.* There are four cells on each of the left, rear, and the right walls, though due to rock fault there are none at the ends of the rear aisle.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The paintings of Cave 1 cover the walls and the ceilings.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] They are in a fair state of preservation, although the full scheme was never completed.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The scenes depicted are mostly didactic, devotional, and ornamental, with scenes from the Jataka stories of the Buddha's former lives as a bodhisattva, the life of the Gautama Buddha, and those of his veneration.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The two most famous individual painted images at Ajanta are the two over-lifesize figures of the protective bodhisattvas Padmapani and Vajrapani on either side of the entrance to the Buddha shrine on the wall of the rear aisle (see illustrations above).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Other significant frescoes in Cave 1 include the Sibi, Sankhapala, Mahajanaka, Mahaummagga, and Champeyya Jataka tales.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave-paintings also show the Temptation of Mara, the miracle of Sravasti where the Buddha simultaneously manifests in many forms, the story of Nanda, and the story of Siddhartha and Yasodhara.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Outside view and main hall with shrine, Cave 2.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 2, adjacent to Cave 1, is known for the paintings that have been preserved on its walls, ceilings, and pillars.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] It looks similar to Cave 1 and is in a better state of preservation.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This cave is best known for its feminine focus, intricate rock carvings and paint artwork yet it is incomplete and lacks consistency.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] One of the 5th-century frescos in this cave also shows children at a school, with those in the front rows paying attention to the teacher, while those in the back row are shown distracted and acting.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 2 (35.7 m × 21.6 m) was started in the 460s, but mostly carved between 475 and 477 CE, probably sponsored and influenced by a woman closely related to emperor Harisena.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] It has a porch quite different from Cave 1.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Even the façade carvings seem to be different.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave is supported by robust pillars, ornamented with designs.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The front porch consists of cells supported by pillared vestibules on both ends.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The hall has four colonnades which are supporting the ceiling and surrounding a square in the center of the hall.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Each arm or colonnade of the square is parallel to the respective walls of the hall, making an aisle in between.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The colonnades have rock-beams above and below them.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The capitals are carved and painted with various decorative themes that include ornamental, human, animal, vegetative, and semi-divine motifs.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Major carvings include that of goddess Hariti.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] She is a Buddhist deity who originally was the demoness of smallpox and a child eater, who the Buddha converted into a guardian goddess of fertility, easy child birth and one who protects babies.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The paintings on the ceilings and walls of Cave 2 have been widely published.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] They depict the Hamsa, Vidhurapandita, Ruru, Kshanti Jataka tales and the Purna Avadhana.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Other frescos show the miracle of Sravasti, Ashtabhaya Avalokitesvara and the dream of Maya.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Just as the stories illustrated in cave 1 emphasise kingship, those in cave 2 show many noble and powerful women in prominent roles, leading to suggestions that the patron was an unknown woman.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The porch's rear wall has a doorway in the center, which allows entrance to the hall.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] On either side of the door is a square-shaped window to brighten the interior.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 3 is merely a start of an excavation; according to Spink it was begun right at the end of the final period of work and soon abandoned.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This is an incomplete monastery and only the preliminary excavations of pillared veranda exist.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave was one of the last projects to start at the site.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Its date could be ascribed to circa 477 CE, just before the sudden death of Emperor Harisena.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The work stopped after the scooping out of a rough entrance of the hall.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 4, a Vihara, was sponsored by Mathura, likely not a noble or courtly official, rather a wealthy devotee.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This is the largest vihara in the inaugural group, which suggests he had immense wealth and influence without being a state official.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] It is placed at a significantly higher level, possibly because the artists realized that the rock quality at the lower and same level of other caves was poor and they had a better chance of a major vihara at an upper location.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Another likely possibility is that the planners wanted to carve into the rock another large cistern to the left courtside for more residents, mirroring the right, a plan implied by the height of the forward cells on the left side.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The Archaeological Survey of India dates it to the 6th century CE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Spink, in contrast, dates this cave's inauguration a century earlier, to about 463 CE, based on construction style and other inscriptions.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 4 shows evidence of a dramatic collapse of its ceiling in the central hall, likely in the 6th century, something caused by the vastness of the cave and geological flaws in the rock.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Later, the artists attempted to overcome this geological flaw by raising the height of the ceiling through deeper excavation of the embedded basalt lava.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave has a squarish plan, houses a colossal image of the Buddha in preaching pose flanked by bodhisattvas and celestial nymphs hovering above.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] It consists, of a verandah, a hypostylar hall, sanctum with an antechamber and a series of unfinished cells.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This monastery is the largest among the Ajanta caves and it measures nearly 970 square metres (10,400 sq ft) (35 m × 28 m).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The door frame is exquisitely sculpted flanking to the right is carved Bodhisattva as reliever of Eight Great Perils.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The rear wall of the veranda contains the panel of litany of Avalokiteśvara.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave's ceiling collapse likely affected its overall plan, caused it being left incomplete.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Only the Buddha's statue and the major sculptures were completed, and except for what the sponsor considered most important elements all other elements inside the cave were never painted.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 5, an unfinished excavation, was planned as a monastery (10.32 × 16.8 m).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 5 is devoid of sculpture and architectural elements except the door frame.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The ornate carvings on the frame has female figures with mythical *makara* creatures found in ancient and medieval-era Indian arts.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave's construction was likely initiated about 465 CE but abandoned because the rock has geological flaws.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The construction was resumed in 475 CE after Asmakas restarted work at the Ajanta caves, but abandoned again as the artists and sponsor redesigned and focussed on an expanded Cave 6 that abuts Cave 5.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] It consists of a sanctum, a hall on both levels.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The lower level is pillared and has attached cells.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The upper hall also has subsidiary cells.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The sanctums on both level feature a Buddha in the teaching posture.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Elsewhere, the Buddha is shown in different mudras.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The lower level walls depict the Miracle of Sravasti and the Temptation of Mara legends.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Only the lower floor of cave 6 was finished.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The unfinished upper floor of cave 6 has many private votive sculptures, and a shrine Buddha.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The lower level of Cave 6 likely was the earliest excavation in the second stage of construction.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This stage marked the Mahayana theme and Vakataka renaissance period of Ajanta reconstruction that started about four centuries after the earlier Hinayana theme construction.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The upper storey was not envisioned in the beginning, it was added as an afterthought, likely around the time when the architects and artists abandoned further work on the geologically flawed rock of Cave 5 immediately next to it.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Both lower and upper Cave 6 show crude experimentation and construction errors.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave work was most likely in progress between 460 and 470 CE, and it is the first that shows attendant Bodhisattvas.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The upper cave construction probably began in 465, progressed swiftly, and much deeper into the rock than the lower level.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The walls and sanctum's door frame of the both levels are intricately carved.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] These show themes such as *makaras* and other mythical creatures, apsaras, elephants in different stages of activity, females in waving or welcoming gesture.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The upper level of Cave 6 is significant in that it shows a devotee in a kneeling posture at the Buddha's feet, an indication of devotional worship practices by the 5th century.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The colossal Buddha of the shrine has an elaborate throne back, but was hastily finished in 477/478 CE, when king Harisena died.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The shrine antechamber of the cave features an unfinished sculptural group of the Six Buddhas of the Past, of which only five statues were carved.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This idea may have been influenced from those in Bagh Caves of Madhya Pradesh.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 7 is also a monastery (15.55 × 31.25 m) but a single storey.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] It consists of a sanctum, a hall with octagonal pillars, and eight small rooms for monks.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The sanctum Buddha is shown in preaching posture.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] There are many art panels narrating Buddhist themes, including those of the Buddha with Nagamuchalinda and Miracle of Sravasti.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 7 has a grand facade with two porticos.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The veranda has eight pillars of two types.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] One has an octagonal base with amalaka and lotus capital.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The other lacks a distinctly shaped base, features an octagonal shaft instead with a plain capital.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] On the left side in this antechamber are seated or standing sculptures such as those of 25 carved seated Buddhas in various postures and facial expressions, while on the right side are 58 seated Buddha reliefs in different postures, all placed on lotus.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] These Buddhas and others on the inner walls of the antechamber are a sculptural depiction of the Miracle of Sravasti in Buddhist theology.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The bottom row shows two *Nagas* (serpents with hoods) holding the blooming lotus stalk.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The antechamber leads to the sanctum through a door frame.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] On this frame are carved two females standing on *makaras* (mythical sea creatures).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Inside the sanctum is the Buddha sitting on a lion throne in cross legged posture, surrounded by other Bodhisattva figures, two attendants with *chauris* (fly-whisks) and flying apsaras above.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Perhaps because of faults in the rock, Cave 7 was never taken very deep into the cliff.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] It consists only of the two porticos and a shrine room with antechamber, with no central hall.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave artwork likely underwent revisions and refurbishments over time.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The first version was complete by about 469 CE, the myriad Buddhas added and painted a few years later between 476 and 478 CE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 8 is small, and located at the lowest level in Ajanta, just below the walkway between Caves 7 and 9.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 8 is another unfinished monastery (15.24 × 24.64 m).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] For many decades in the 20th century, this cave was used as a storage and generator room.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] It is at the river level with easy access, relatively lower than other caves, and according to Archaeological Survey of India it is possibly one of the earliest monasteries.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Much of its front is damaged, likely from a landslide.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave excavation proved difficult and probably abandoned after a geological fault consisting of a mineral layer proved disruptive to stable carvings.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Spink, in contrast, states that Cave 8 is perhaps the earliest cave from the second period, its shrine an "afterthought".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] It may well be the oldest Mahayana monastery excavated in India, according to Spink.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The statue may have been loose rather than carved from the living rock, as it has now vanished.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave was painted, but only traces remain.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Caves 9 and 10 are the two *chaitya* or worship halls from the 2nd to 1st century BCE – the first period of construction, though both were reworked upon the end of the second period of construction in the 5th century CE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This has led Spink to the view that Cave 10 was perhaps originally of the 1st century BCE, and cave 9 about a hundred years later.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The small "shrinelets" called caves 9A to 9D and 10A also date from the second period.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 9 arch has remnant profile that suggests that it likely had wooden fittings.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave has a distinct apsidal shape, nave, aisle and an apse with an icon, architecture, and plan that reminds one of the cathedrals built in Europe many centuries later.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The stupa is at the center of the apse, with a circumambulation path around it.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] The stupa sits on a high cylindrical base.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] On the left wall of the cave are votaries approaching the stupa, which suggests a devotional tradition.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink, the paintings in this cave, including the intrusive standing Buddhas on the pillars, were added in the 5th century.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] On the walls are friezes of Jataka tales, but likely from the Hinayana phase of early construction.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] Some of the panels and reliefs inside as well as outside Cave 10 do not make narrative sense, but are related to Buddhist legends.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This lack of narrative flow may be because these were added by different monks and official donors in the 5th century wherever empty space was available.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p01] This devotionalism and the worship hall character of this cave is the likely reason why four additional shrinelets 9A, 9B, 9C, and 9D were added between Cave 9 and 10.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 10, a vast prayer hall or Chaitya, is dated to about the 1st century BCE, together with the nearby vihara cave No 12.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] These two caves are thus among the earliest of the Ajanta complex.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It has a large central apsidal hall with a row of 39 octagonal pillars, a nave separating its aisle and stupa at the end for worship.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The stupa has a *pradakshina patha* (circumambulatory path).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] This cave is significant because its scale confirms the influence of Buddhism in South Asia by the 1st century BCE and its continued though declining influence in India through the 5th century CE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Further, the cave includes a number of inscriptions where parts of the cave are "gifts of prasada" by different individuals, which in turn suggests that the cave was sponsored as a community effort rather than a single king or one elite official.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 10 is also historically important because in April 1819, a British Army officer John Smith saw its arch and introduced his discovery to the attention of the Western audience.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Several others caves were also built in Western India around the same period under royal sponsorship.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It is thought that the chronology of these early Chaitya Caves is as follows: first Cave 9 at Kondivite Caves and then Cave 12 at the Bhaja Caves, which both predate Cave 10 of Ajanta.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 10 features a Sanskrit inscription in Brahmi script that is archaeologically important.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The inscription is the oldest of the Ajanta site, the Brahmi letters being paleographically dated to circa the 2nd century BCE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] These mostly avoided over-painting the "official" programme and after the best positions were used up are tucked away in less prominent positions not yet painted; the total of these (including those now lost) was probably over 300, and the hands of many different artists are visible.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The paintings are numerous and from two periods, many narrating the Jataka tales in a clockwise sequence.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Both Hinayana and Mahayana stage paintings are discernable, though the former are more faded and begrimed with early centuries of Hinayana worship.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Of interest here is the Saddanta Jataka tale – the fable about six tusked elephant, and the Shyama Jataka – the story about the man who dedicates his life serving his blind parents.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Stella Kramrisch, the oldest layer of the Cave 10 paintings date from about 100 BCE, and the principles behind their composition are analogous to those from the same era at Sanchi and Amaravati.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave veranda has pillars with octagonal shafts and square bases.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The ceiling of the veranda shows evidence of floral designs and eroded reliefs.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Only the center panel is discernible wherein the Buddha is seen with votaries lining up to pray before him.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Inside, the cave consists of a hall with a long rock bench opening into six rooms.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Similar stone benches are found in Nasik Caves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Another pillared verandah ends in a sanctum with seated Buddha against an incomplete stupa, and has four cells.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave has a few paintings showing Bodhisattvas and the Buddha.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Of these, the Padmapani, a couple gathered to pray, a pair of peafowl, and a female figure painting have survived in the best condition.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The sanctum of this cave may be among the last structures built at Ajanta because it features a circumambulation path around the seated Buddha.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Archaeological Survey of India (ASI), Cave 12 is an early stage Hinayana (Theravada) monastery (14.9 × 17.82 m) from the 2nd to 1st century BCE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Spink however only dates it to the 1st century BCE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave is damaged with its front wall completely collapsed.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Its three sides inside have twelve cells, each with two stone beds.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 13 is another small monastery from the early period, consisting of a hall with seven cells, each also with two stone beds, all carved out of the rock.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Each cell has rock-cut beds for the monks.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] In contrast to ASI's estimate, Gupte and Mahajan date both these caves about two to three centuries later, between 1st and 2nd-century CE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 14 is another unfinished monastery (13.43 × 19.28 m) but carved above Cave 13.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The entrance door frame shows *sala bhanjikas*.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 15 is a more complete monastery (19.62 × 15.98 m) with evidence that it had paintings.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave consists of an eight-celled hall ending in a sanctum, an antechamber and a verandah with pillars.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The reliefs show the Buddha, while the sanctum Buddha is shown seated in the Simhasana posture.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 15 door frame has carvings of pigeons eating grain.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 15A is the smallest cave with a hall and one cell on each side.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Its entrance is just to the right of the elephant-decorated entrance to Cave 16.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It is an ancient Hinayana cave with three cells opening around a minuscule central hall.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The doors are decorated with a rail and arch pattern.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It had an inscription in an ancient script, which has been lost.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Entrance stairs to the single-storey Cave 16, with stone elephants and front with pillars (left).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Inside hall with seated Buddha statue (right).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 16 occupies a prime position near the middle of site, and was sponsored by Varahadeva, minister of Vakataka king Harishena (r. c.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] He was, states Spink, probably someone who revered both the Buddha and the Hindu gods, as he proclaims his Hindu heritage in an inscription in the nearby Ghatotkacha Cave.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The 7th-century Chinese traveler Xuan Zang described the cave as the entrance to the site.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 16 (19.5 m × 22.25 m × 4.6 m) influenced the architecture of the entire site.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Spink and other scholars call it the "crucial cave" that helps trace the chronology of the second and closing stages of the entire cave's complex construction.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 16 is a Mahayana monastery and has the standard arrangement of a main doorway, two windows, and two aisle doorways.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The veranda of this monastery is 19.5 m × 3 m, while the main hall is almost a perfect square with 19.5 m side.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Narratives include various Jataka tales such as Hasti, Mahaummagga and the Sutasoma fables.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Other frescos depict the conversion of Nanda, miracle of Sravasti, Sujata's offering, Asita's visit, the dream of Maya, the Trapusha and Bhallika story, and the ploughing festival.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The Hasti Jataka frescos tell the story of a Bodhisattva elephant who learns of a large group of people starving, then tells them to go below a cliff where they could find food.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The elephant proceeds to sacrifice himself by jumping off that cliff thereby becoming food so that the people can survive.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] These frescos are found immediately to the left of entrance, in the front corridor and the narrative follows a clockwise direction.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The Mahaummagga Jataka frescos are found on the left wall of the corridor, which narrates the story of a child Bodhisattva.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Thereafter, in the left corridor is the legend surrounding the conversion of Nanda – the half brother of the Buddha.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The story depicted is one of the two major versions of the Nanda legend in the Buddhist tradition, one where Nanda wants to lead a sensuous life with the girl he had just wed and the Buddha takes him to heaven and later hell to show the spiritual dangers of a sensual life.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] After the Nanda-related frescos, the cave presents Manushi Buddhas, followed by flying votaries with offerings to worship the Buddha and the Buddha seated in teaching asana and *dharma chakra mudra*.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The right wall of the corridor show the scenes from the life of the Buddha.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] These include Sujata offering food to the Buddha with a begging bowl in white dress, Tapussa and Bhalluka next to the Buddha after they offering wheat and honey to the Buddha as monk, the future Buddha sitting alone under a tree, and the Buddha at a ploughing festival.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] One mural shows Buddha's parents trying to dissuade him from becoming a monk.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Another shows the Buddha at the palace surrounded by men in *dhoti* and women in *sari* as his behavior presents the four signs that he is likely to renounce.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] On this side of the corridor are also paintings that show the future Buddha as a baby with sage Asita with rishi-like looks.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Spink, some of the Cave 16 paintings were left incomplete.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 17 (34.5 m × 25.63 m) along with Cave 16 with two great stone elephants at the entrance and Cave 26 with sleeping Buddha, were some of the many caves sponsored by the Hindu Vakataka prime minister Varahadeva.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 17 had additional donors such as the local king Upendragupta, as evidenced by the inscription therein.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave features a large and most sophisticated vihara design, along with some of the best-preserved and well-known paintings of all the caves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] While Cave 16 is known for depicting the life stories of the Buddha, the Cave 17 paintings has attracted much attention for extolling human virtues by narrating the Jataka tales.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The narration includes attention to details and a realism which Stella Kramrisch calls "lavish elegance" accomplished by efficient craftsmen.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The ancient artists, states Kramrisch, tried to show wind passing over a crop by showing it bending in waves, and a similar profusion of rhythmic sequences that unroll story after story, visually presenting the metaphysical.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The Cave 17 monastery includes a colonnaded porch, a number of pillars each with a distinct style, a peristyle design for the interior hall, a shrine antechamber located deep in the cave, larger windows and doors for more light, along with extensive integrated carvings of Indian gods and goddesses.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The hall of this monastery is a 380.53 square metres (4,096.0 sq ft) square, with 20 pillars.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The grand scale of the carving also introduced errors of taking out too much rock to shape the walls, states Spink, which led to the cave being splayed out toward the rear.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 17 has one long inscription by king Upendragupta, in which he explains that he has "expended abundant wealth" on building this vihara, bringing much satisfaction to the devotees.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Altogether, Upendragupta is known to have sponsored at least 5 of the caves in Ajanta.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] He may have spent too much wealth on religious pursuits however, as he was ultimately defeated by the attacks of the Asmaka.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The paintings of Cave 17 depict Buddha in various forms and postures – Vipasyi, Sikhi, Visvbhu, Krakuchchanda, Kanakamuni, Kashyapa and Sakyamuni.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Also depicted are Avalokitesvara, the story of Udayin and Gupta, the story of Nalagiri, the Wheel of life, a panel celebrating various ancient Indian musicians and a panel that tells the tales of Prince Simhala's expedition to Sri Lanka.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The narrative frescos depict the various Jataka tales such as the Shaddanta, Hasti, Hamsa, Vessantara, Sutasoma, Mahakapi (in two versions), Sarabhamiga, Machchha, Matiposaka, Shyama, Mahisha, Valahassa, Sibi, Ruru and Nigrodamiga Jatakas.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The depictions weave in the norms of the early 1st millennium culture and the society.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] They show themes as diverse as a shipwreck, a princess applying makeup, lovers in scenes of dalliance, and a wine drinking scene of a couple with the woman and man amorously seated.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Some frescos attempt to show the key characters from various parts of a Jataka tale by co-depicting animals and attendants in the same scene.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 18 is a small rectangular space (3.38 × 11.66 m) with two octagonal pillars and it joins another cell.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Entrance façade and inside worship hall, Cave 19, sponsored by king Upendragupta.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 19 is a worship hall (chaitya griha, 16.05 × 7.09 m) datable to the fifth century CE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The hall shows painted Buddha, depicted in different postures.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] This worship hall is now visited through what was previously a carved room.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The presence of this room before the hall suggests that the original plan included a mandala style courtyard for devotees to gather and wait, an entrance and facade to this courtyard, all of whose ruins are now lost to history.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 19 is one of the caves known for its sculpture.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It includes Naga figures with a serpent canopy protecting the Buddha, similar to those found for spiritual icons in the ancient Jain and Hindu traditions.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It includes Yaksha dwarapala (guardian) images on the side of its vetayana (arches), flying couples, sitting Buddha, standing Buddhas and evidence that its ceiling was once painted.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 19 drew upon on the plan and experimentation in Cave 9.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 19 excavation and stupa was likely in place by 467 CE, and its finishing and artistic work continued into the early 470s, but it too was an incomplete cave when it was dedicated in 471 CE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The entrance facade of the Cave 19 worship hall is ornate.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Two round pillars with fluted floral patterns and carved garlands support a porch.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Its capital is an inverted lotus connecting to an *amalaka*.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] To its left is standing Buddha in *varada hasta mudra* with a devotee prostrating at his feet.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] On right is a relief of woman with one hand holding a pitcher and other touching her chin.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Above is a seated Buddha in meditating mudra.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Towards the right of the entrance is the "Mother and Child" sculpture.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] A figure with begging bowl is the Buddha, watching him are his wife and son.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The worship hall is apsidal, with 15 pillars dividing it into two side aisles and one nave.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The round pillars have floral reliefs and a fluted shaft topped with Buddha in its capitals.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Next, to the Buddha in the capitals are elephants, horses and flying apsara friezes found elsewhere in India, reflecting the style of the Gupta Empire artwork.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Sharma, the similarities at the Karla Caves Great Chaitya, built in the 2nd century CE, suggest that Cave 19 may have been modeled after it.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The walls and the ceiling of the side aisles inside the worship hall are covered with paintings.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] These show the Buddha, flowers, and in the left aisle the "Mother and Child" legend again.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 20 is a monastery hall (16.2 × 17.91 m) from the 5th century.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Its construction, states Spink, was started in the 460s by king Upendragupta, with his expressed desire "to make the great tree of religious merit grow".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The work on Cave 20 was pursued in parallel with other caves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 20 has exquisite detailing, states Spink, but it was relatively lower on priority than Caves 17 and 19.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The work on Cave 20 was intermittently stopped and then continued in the following decade.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The vihara consists of a sanctum, four cells for monks and a pillared verandah with two stone cut windows for light.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Prior to entering the main hall, on the left of veranda are two Buddhas carved above the window and side cell.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The ceiling of the main hall has remnants of painting.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The sanctum Buddha is in preaching posture.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave is known for the sculpture showing seven Buddhas with attendants on its lintel.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave has a dedicatory Sanskrit inscription in Brahmi script in its verandah, and it calls the cave as a *mandapa*.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Many of the figural and ornamental carvings in Cave 20 are similar to Cave 19, and to a lesser degree to those found in Cave 17.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] This may be because the same architects and artisans were responsible for the evolution of the three caves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The door frames in Cave 20 are quasi-structural, something unique at the Ajanta site.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The decorations are also innovative in Cave 20, such as one showing the Buddha seated against two pillows and "a richly laden mango tree behind him", states Spink.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 21 is a hall (29.56 × 28.03 m) with twelve rock-cut rooms for monks, a sanctum, and twelve pillared and pilastered verandah.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The carvings on the pilaster include those of animals and flowers.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The pillars feature reliefs of apsaras, Nagaraja, and Nagarani, as well as devotees bowing with the Anjali mudra.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The hall shows evidence that it used to be completely painted.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 22 is a small vihara (12.72 × 11.58 m) with a narrow veranda and four unfinished cells.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It is excavated at a higher level and has to be reached by a flight of steps.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Inside, the Buddha is seated in pralamba-padasana.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The painted figures in Cave 22 show Manushi-Buddhas with Maitreya.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] A pilaster on the left side of the Cave 22 veranda has a Sanskrit prose inscription.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It is damaged in parts, and the legible parts state that this is a "meritorious gift of a mandapa by Jayata", calling Jayata's family as "a great Upasaka", and ending the inscription with "may the merit of this be for excellent knowledge to all sentient beings, beginning with father and mother".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 23 is also unfinished, consisting of a hall (28.32 × 22.52 m) but a design similar to Cave 21.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave differs in its pillar decorations and the naga doorkeepers.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Exterior, and unfinished inside of Cave 24.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 24 is like Cave 21, unfinished but much larger.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It features the second largest monastery hall (29.3 × 29.3 m) after Cave 4.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave 24 monastery has been important to scholarly studies of the site because it shows how multiple crews of workers completed their objectives in parallel.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The cell construction began as soon as the aisle had been excavated and while the main hall and sanctum were under construction.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The construction of Cave 24 was planned in 467 CE, but likely started in 475 CE, with support from Buddhabhadra, then abruptly ended in 477 with the sponsor king Harisena's death.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It is significant in having one of the most complex capitals on a pillar at the Ajanta site, an indication of how the artists excelled and continuously improved their sophistication as they worked with the rock inside the cave.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The artists carved fourteen complex miniature figures on the central panel of the right center porch pillar, while working in dim light in a cramped cave space.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The medallion reliefs in Cave 24 similarly show loving couples and anthropomorphic arts, rather than flowers of earlier construction.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 24's sanctum has a seated Buddha in pralamba-padasana.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Its hall (11.37 × 12.24 m) is similar to other monasteries, but has no sanctum, includes an enclosed courtyard and is excavated at an upper level.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 26 is a worship hall (chaityagriha, 25.34 × 11.52 m) similar in plan to Cave 19.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It is much larger and with elements of a vihara design.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] An inscription states that a monk Buddhabhadra and his friend minister serving king of Asmaka gifted this vast cave.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The inscription includes a vision statement and the aim to make "a memorial on the mountain that will endure for as long as the moon and the sun continue", translates Walter Spink.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It is likely that the builders focussed on sculpture, rather than paintings, in Cave 26 because they believed stone sculpture will far more endure than paintings on the wall.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The sculptures in Cave 26 are elaborate and more intricate.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It is among the last caves excavated, and an inscription suggests late 5th or early 6th century according to ASI.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave consists of an apsidal hall with side aisles for circumambulation (*pradikshana*).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] This path is full of carved Buddhist legends, three depictions of the Miracle of Sravasti in the right ambulatory side of the aisle, and seated Buddhas in various mudra.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Many of these were added later by devotees, and therefore are intrusive to the aims of the original planners.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The artwork begins on the wall of the aisle, immediately the left side of entrance.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The major artworks include the Mahaparinirvana of Buddha (reclining Buddha) on the wall, followed by the legend called the "Temptations by Mara".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The temptations include the seduction by Mara's daughters who are depicted below the meditating Buddha.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] They are shown scantly dressed and in seductive postures, while on both the left and right side of the Buddha are armies of Mara attempting to distract him with noise and threaten him with violence.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] In the top right corner is the image of a dejected Mara frustrated by his failure to disturb the resolve or focus of the ascetic Buddha.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] At the center of the apse is a rock-cut stupa.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The stupa has an image of the Buddha on its front, 18 panels on its base, 18 panels above these, a three tiered *torana* above him, and apsaras are carved on the *anda* (hemispherical egg) stupa.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] On top of the dagoba is a nine-tiered *harmika*, a symbolism for the nine saṃsāra (Buddhism) heavens in Mahayana cosmology.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The walls, pillars, brackets and the triforium are extensively carved with Buddhist themes.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Many of the wall reliefs and images in this cave were badly damaged, and have been restored as a part of the site conservation efforts.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Between cave 26 and its left wing, there is an inscription by a courtier of Rashtrakuta Nanaraj (who is mentioned in the Multai and Sangaloda plates), from late 7th or early 8th century.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 27 is a monastery and may have been planned as an attachment to Cave 26.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Its two storeys are damaged, with the upper level partially collapsed.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Its plan is similar to other monasteries.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] : Cave 28, further beyond Cave 27, at the westernmost end of the Ajanta complex.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] : Cave 29, high up between caves 20 and 21.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 28 is an unfinished monastery, partially excavated, at the westernmost end of the Ajanta complex and barely accessible.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 29 an unfinished monastery at the highest level of the Ajanta complex, apparently unnoticed when the initial numbering system was established, and physically located between Caves 20 and 21.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] In 1956, a landslide covered the footpath leading to Cave 16.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] In the attempts to clear and restore the walkway, a small aperture and votive stupa were noticed in the debris by the workers, in a location near the stream bed.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Further tracing and excavations led to a previously unknown Hinayana monastery cave dated to the 2nd and 1st century BCE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 30 may actually be the oldest cave of the Ajanta complex.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It is a 3.66 m × 3.66 m cave with three cells, each with two stone beds and stone pillows on the side of each cell.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The cell door lintels show lotus and garland carvings.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave has two inscriptions in an unknown script.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It also has a platform on its veranda with a fine view of the river ravine below and the forest cover.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Gupte and Mahajan, this cave may have been closed at some point with large carefully carved pieces as it distracted the entrance view of Cave 16.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Over 80% of the Ajanta caves were *vihara* (temporary traveler residences, monasteries).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The designers and artisans who built these caves included facilities for collecting donations and storing grains and food for the visitors and monks.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Many of the caves include large repositories cut into the floor.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The largest storage spaces are found, states Spink, in the "very commodious recesses in the shrines of both Ajanta Cave Lower 6 and Cave 11".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] These caves were probably chosen because of their relative convenience and the security they offered due to their higher level.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The choice of integrating covered vaults cut into the floor may have been driven by the need to provide sleeping space.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] A burnt-brick vihara monastery facing the caves on the right bank of the river Waghora has been recently excavated.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It has a number of cells facing a central courtyard, in which a stupa was established.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] A coin of the Western Satraps ruler Visvasena (ruled 293–304 CE) as well as a gold coin of the Byzantine Emperor Theodosius II (ruled 402-450 CE) were found in the excavations, giving further numismatic confirmation for the dating of the caves.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] A terracotta plaque of Mahishasuramardini was also found, which was possibly under worship by the artisans.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The paintings have deteriorated significantly since they were rediscovered, and a number of 19th-century copies and drawings are important for a complete understanding of the works.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] A number of attempts to copy the Ajanta paintings began in the 19th century for European and Japanese museums.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Some of these works have later been lost in natural and fire disasters.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] In 1846 for example, Major Robert Gill, an Army officer from Madras Presidency and a painter, was appointed by the Royal Asiatic Society to make copies of the frescos on the cave walls.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Gill worked on his painting at the site from 1844 to 1863.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] He made 27 copies of large sections of murals, but all but four were destroyed in a fire at the Crystal Palace in London in 1866, where they were on display.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Gill returned to the site, and recommenced his labours, replicating the murals until his death in 1875.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Another attempt was made in 1872 when the Bombay Presidency commissioned John Griffiths to work with his students to make copies of Ajanta paintings, again for shipping to England.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] They worked on this for thirteen years and some 300 canvases were produced, many of which were displayed at the Imperial Institute on Exhibition Road in London, one of the forerunners of the Victoria and Albert Museum.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] But in 1885 another fire destroyed over a hundred of the paintings in storage in a wing of the museum.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The V&A still has 166 paintings surviving from both sets, though none have been on permanent display since 1955.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The largest are some 3 by 6 metres (9.8 ft × 19.7 ft).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] A conservation project was undertaken on about half of them in 2006, also involving the University of Northumbria.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Griffith and his students had painted many of the paintings with "cheap varnish" in order to make them easier to see, which has added to the deterioration of the originals, as has, according to Spink and others, recent cleaning by the ASI.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] A further set of copies was made between 1909 and 1911 by Christiana Herringham (Lady Herringham) and a group of students from the Calcutta School of Art that included the future Indian Modernist painter Nandalal Bose.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The copies were published in full colour as the first publication of London's fledgling India Society.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] More than the earlier copies, these aimed to fill in holes and damage to recreate the original condition rather than record the state of the paintings as she was seeing them.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] According to one writer, unlike the paintings created by her predecessors Griffiths and Gill, whose copies were influenced by British Victorian styles of painting, those of the Herringham expedition preferred an 'Indian Renascence' aesthetic of the type pioneered by Abanindranath Tagore.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Early photographic surveys were made by Robert Gill, whose photos, including some using stereoscopy, were used in books by him and Fergusson (many are available online from the British Library), then Victor Goloubew in 1911 and E.L.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Vassey, who took the photos in the four volume study of the caves by Ghulam Yazdani (published 1930–1955).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Some slightly creative copies of Ajanta frescos, especially the painting of the Adoration of the Buddha from the shrine antechamber of Cave 17, were commissioned by Thomas Holbein Hendley (1847–1917) for the decoration of the walls of the hall of the Albert Hall Museum, Jaipur, India.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] He had the work painted by a local artist variously named Murli or Murali.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The museum was opened to the public in 1887.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] This work is otherwise presented as characteristic of the end of the 19th century.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Another attempt to make copies of the murals was made by the Japanese artist Arai Kampō (荒井寛方:1878–1945) after being invited by Rabindranath Tagore to India to teach Japanese painting techniques.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] He worked on making copies with tracings on Japanese paper from 1916 to 1918 and his work was conserved at Tokyo Imperial University until the materials perished during the 1923 Great Kantō earthquake.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] heading to a temple, five women chatting in a market square, children playing a board game near a banana tree.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The Ajanta cave arts are a window into the culture, society and religiosity of the native population of India between the 2nd century BCE and 5th century CE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Different scholars have variously interpreted them from the perspective of gender studies, history, sociology, and the anthropology of South Asia.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The dress, the jewellery, the gender relations, the social activities depicted show at least the lifestyle of the royalty and elite, and in others definitely the costumes of the common man, monks and rishi.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] They shine "light on life in India" around mid 1st millennium CE.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The Ajanta paintings provide a contrast between the spiritual life of monks who had given up all materialistic possessions versus the sensual life of those it considered materialistic, luxurious, symbols of wealth, leisurely and high fashion.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Many frescos show scenes from shops, festivals, jesters at processions, palaces and performance art pavilions.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] These friezes share themes and details of those found in Bharhut, Sanchi, Amaravati, Ellora, Bagh, Aihole, Badami and other archaeological sites in India.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Ajanta caves contributes to visual and descriptive sense of the ancient and early medieval Indian culture and artistic traditions, particularly those around the Gupta Empire era period.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The earliest colonial era descriptions of the Ajanta caves was largely orientalist and critical.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] According to William Dalrymple, the subjects in the Ajanta caves were puzzling to 19th-century Orientalists.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Lacking the Asian cultural heritage and with no knowledge of Jataka Tales or equivalent Indian fables, they could not comprehend it.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] They projected their own views and assumptions, calling it something that lacks reason and rationale, something that is a meaningless crude representation of royalty and foreigners with mysticism and sensuousness.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The 19th-century views and interpretations of the Ajanta Caves were conditioned by ideas and assumptions in the colonial mind, saw what they wanted to see.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] To many who are unaware of the premises of Indian religions in general, and Buddhism in particular, the significance of Ajanta Caves has been like the rest of Indian art.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Richard Cohen, the Ajanta Caves to them has been yet another example of "worship this stock, or that stone, or monstrous idol".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] In contrast, to the Indian mind and the larger Buddhist community, it is everything that art ought to be, the religious and the secular, the spiritual and the social fused to enlightened perfection.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Walter Spink – one of the most respected Art historians on Ajanta, these caves were by 475 CE a much-revered site to the Indians, with throngs of "travelers, pilgrims, monks and traders".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The site was vastly transformed into its current form in just 20 years, between early 460 CE to early 480 CE, by regional architects and artisans.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] This accomplishment, states Spink, makes Ajanta, "one of the most remarkable creative achievements in man's history".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The Ajanta Caves painting are a significant source of socio-economic information in ancient India, particularly in relation to the interactions of India with foreign cultures at the time most of the paintings were made, in the 5th century CE (Common Era).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Indian historian Haroon Khan Sherwani: "The paintings at Ajanta clearly demonstrate the cosmopolitan character of Buddhism, which opened its way to men of all races, Greek, Persian, Saka, Pahlava, Kushan and Huna".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Depictions of foreigners abound: according to Spink, "Ajanta's paintings are filled with such foreign types." They have sometimes been a source of misinterpretation as in the so-called "Persian Embassy Scene".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] These foreigners may reflect the Sassanian merchants, visitors and the flourishing trade routes of the day.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 1, for example, shows a mural fresco with characters with foreigner faces or dresses, the so-called "Persian Embassy Scene".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] This scene is located at the right of the entrance door upon entering the hall.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Spink, James Fergusson, a 19th-century architectural historian, had decided that this scene corresponded to the Persian ambassador in 625 CE to the court of the Hindu Chalukya king Pulakeshin II.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] An alternate theory has been that the fresco represents a Hindu ambassador visiting the Persian king Khusrau II in 625 CE, a theory that Fergusson disagreed with.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 1 has several frescos with characters with foreigners' faces or dresses.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Similar depictions are found in the paintings of Cave 17.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Such murals, states Pia Brancaccio, suggest a prosperous and multicultural society in 5th-century India active in international trade.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] These also suggest that this trade was economically important enough to the Deccan region that the artists chose to include it with precision.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Additional evidence of international trade includes the use of the blue lapis lazuli pigment to depict foreigners in the Ajanta paintings, which must have been imported from Afghanistan or Iran.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] It also suggests, states Brancaccio, that the Buddhist monastic world was closely connected with trading guilds and the court culture in this period.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] A small number of scenes show foreigners drinking wine in Caves 1 and 2.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Some show foreign Near East kings with wine and their retinue which presumably add to the "general regal emphasis" of the cave.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Brancaccio, the Ajanta paintings show a variety of colorful, delicate textiles and women making cotton.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Textile probably was one of the major exports to foreign lands, along with gems.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] These were exported first through the Red Sea, and later through the Persian Gulf, thereby bringing a period of economic and cultural exchange between the Indians, the Sasanian Empire and the Persian merchants before Islam was founded in the Arabian peninsula.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] While scholars generally agree that these murals confirm trade and cultural connections between India and Sassanian west, their specific significance and interpretation varies.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Brancaccio, for example, suggests that the ship and jars in them probably reflect foreign ships carrying wine imported to India.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] In contrast, Schlinghoff interprets the jars to be holding water, and ships shown as Indian ships used in international trade.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Similar depictions are found in the paintings of Cave 17, but this time in direct relation to the worship of the Buddha.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] In Cave 17, a painting of the Buddha descending from the Trayastrimsa Heaven shows he being attended by many foreigners.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Many foreigners in this painting are thus shown as listeners to the Buddhist Dharma.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The ethnic diversity is depicted in the painting in the clothes (kaftans, Sasanian helmets, round caps), hairdos and skin colors.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] In the Visvantara Jataka of Cave 17, according to Brancaccio, the scene probably shows a servant from Central Asia holding a foreign metal ewer, while a dark-complexioned servant holds a cup to an amorous couple.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] In another painting in Cave 17, relating to the conversion of Nanda, a man possibly from northeast Africa appears as a servant.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] These representations show, states Brancaccio, that the artists were familiar with people of Sogdia, Central Asia, Persia and possibly East Africa.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Another hypothesis is offered by Upadhya, who states that the artists who built Ajanta caves "very probably included foreigners".
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The Ajanta paintings, or more likely the general style they come from, influenced painting in Tibet and Sri Lanka.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Some influences from Ajanta have also suggested in the Kizil Caves of the Tarim Basin, in particular in early caves such as the *Peacock Cave*.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] The rediscovery of ancient Indian paintings at Ajanta provided Indian artists with examples from ancient India to follow.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Nandalal Bose experimented with techniques to follow the ancient style which allowed him to develop his unique style.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Abanindranath Tagore and Syed Thajudeen also used the Ajanta paintings for inspiration.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Anna Pavlova's ballet *Ajanta's Frescoes* was inspired by her visit to Ajanta, choreographed by Ivan Clustine, with music by Nikolai Tcherepnin (one report says Mikhail Fokine in 1923). and premiered at Covent Garden in 1923.
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Jewish American poet Muriel Rukeyser wrote about the caves in "Ajanta," the opening poem of her third collection *Beast in View* (1944).
[src:cotton-gin/ajanta-caves-p02] Rukeyser was inspired in part by writings on the caves by artist Mukul Dey in 1925 and art historian Stella Kramrisch in 1937.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] The ***Antebellum* South** era (from Latin: *ante bellum*, lit.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] 'before the war') was a period in the history of the Southern United States that extended from the conclusion of the War of 1812 to the start of the American Civil War in 1861.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] This era was marked by the prevalent practice of human chattel slavery and the associated societal norms it cultivated.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Over the course of this period, Southern leaders underwent a transformation in their perspective on slavery.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Initially regarded as an awkward and temporary institution, it gradually evolved into a defended concept, with proponents arguing for its positive merits, while simultaneously vehemently opposing the burgeoning abolitionist movement.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Southern society was stratified, inegalitarian, and perceived by immigrants as lacking in opportunities.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Consequently, the manufacturing base lagged behind that of the non-slave states.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Wealth inequality grew as the larger landholders took the greater share of the profits generated by enslaved persons, which also helped to entrench their power as a political class.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] As the country expanded westward, slavery's propagation became a major issue in national politics, eventually boiling over into the Civil War.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] In the years that followed the Civil War, the war was romanticized by historical revisionists to protect three central assertions: that the Confederate cause was heroic, that enslaved people were happy and satisfied, and that slavery was not the primary cause of the war.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] This phenomenon has continued to the present day to contribute to racism, gender roles, and religious attitudes in the South, and to a lesser extent in the rest of the United States.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] In the 18th century, the Atlantic slave trade brought enslaved Africans to the South during the colonial period as a source of labor for the harvesting of crops.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] There were almost 700,000 enslaved persons in the U.S. in 1790, which was approximately 18 percent of the total population or roughly one in six people.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] By the end of the 18th century, slavery was in decline, with states in the North beginning to ban the institution and planters in the South realizing that they had no crops successful enough to make slavery financially viable.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] This would change with the invention of the cotton gin by Eli Whitney in the mid-1790s, which changed a once-tedious manual cleaning and fiber separation process into a faster, less labor-intensive procedure.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Suddenly, cotton could be processed more inexpensively and efficiently, resulting in slavery becoming very profitable and a large plantation system developing to support the expanding industry.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] In the 15 years between the invention of the cotton gin and the passage of the Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves, the slave trade increased and slavery became more prevalent in the southern United States.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] The Antebellum South saw large expansions in agriculture during the early 19th century, spurred on by increased demand for cotton for the new textile factories of the industrial North.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] In light of the successful cotton industry, anti-industrial and anti-urban attitudes resulting from a belief that agrarian life would continue to be the best way forward, the Southern economy experienced little industrialization or other manufacturing development.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] The Southern economy was characterized by a low level of capital accumulation (largely slave-labor-based) and a shortage of liquid capital, which led to a South dependent on export trade.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] This was in contrast to the North and West, which relied on their own domestic markets.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Since the Southern domestic market consisted primarily of plantations focused on a few specific crops, Southern states imported sustenance commodities from the West and manufactured goods from England and the North.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] The plantation system can be seen as the factory system applied to agriculture, with a concentration of labor under skilled management.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] But while the industrial manufacturing-based labor economy of the North was driven by growing demand, maintenance of the plantation economic system depended upon slave labor, which was abundant and inexpensive.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] The five major commodities of the Southern agricultural economy were cotton, grain, tobacco, sugar, and rice, with cotton the leading cash crop.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] These commodities were concentrated in the Deep South (Mississippi, Alabama, and Louisiana).
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] The leading historian of the era was Ulrich Bonnell Phillips, who studied slavery not so much as a political issue between North and South, but as a social and economic system.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] He focused on the large plantations that dominated the South.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Phillips addressed the unprofitability of slave labor and slavery's ill effects on the Southern economy.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] An example of pioneering comparative work was *A Jamaica Slave Plantation* (1914).
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] His methods inspired the "Phillips school" of slavery studies, between 1900 and 1950.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Phillips argued that large-scale plantation slavery was inefficient and not progressive.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] It had reached its geographical limits by 1860 or so, and therefore eventually had to fade away (as happened in Brazil).
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] In *The Decadence of the Plantation System* (1910), he argued that slavery was an unprofitable relic that persisted because it produced social status, honor, and political power.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Phillips contended that masters treated enslaved persons relatively well; his views on that issue were later sharply rejected by Kenneth M.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] His conclusions about the economic decline of slavery were challenged in 1958 by Alfred H.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Meyer in a landmark study published in the *Journal of Political Economy*.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Their arguments were further developed by Robert Fogel and Stanley L.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Engerman, who argued in their 1974 book, *Time on the Cross,* that slavery was both efficient and profitable, as long as the price of cotton was high enough.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] In turn, Fogel and Engerman came under attack from other historians of slavery.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] As slavery began to displace indentured servitude as the principal supply of labor in the plantation systems of the South, the economic nature of the institution of slavery aided in the increased inequality of wealth seen in the Antebellum South.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] The demand for slave labor and the U.S. ban on importing more slaves from Africa drove up prices for slaves, making it profitable for smaller farms in older settled areas such as Virginia to sell their slaves further south and west.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] The actuarial risk, or the potential loss in investment of owning slaves from death, disability, etc. was much greater for small plantation owners.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Accentuated by the rise in price of slaves seen just prior to the Civil War, the overall costs associated with owning slaves to the individual plantation owner led to the concentration of slave ownership seen at the eve of the Civil War.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Much of the Antebellum South was rural, and in line with the plantation system, largely agricultural.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] With the exception of New Orleans, Louisiana, Charleston, South Carolina, Richmond, Virginia, and Louisville, Kentucky the slave states had no large cities, and the urban population of the South could not compare to that of the Northeast, or even that of the agrarian West.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] This led to a sharp division in class in the southern states, between the landowning "master" class, yeoman farmers, poor whites, and slaves; while in the northern and western states, much of the social spectrum was dominated by a wide range of different laboring classes.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] The conclusion that, while both the North and the South were characterized by a high degree of inequality during the plantation era, the wealth distribution was much more unequal in the South than in the North arises from studies concerned with the equality of land, slave, and wealth distribution.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] For example, in certain states and counties, due to the concentration of landholding and slave holding, which were highly correlated, six percent of landowners eventually commanding one-third of the gross income and an even higher portion of the net income.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] The majority of landowners, who had smaller scale plantations, saw a disproportionately small portion in revenues generated by the slavery-driven plantation system.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] While the two largest classes in the South included land- and slave-owners and slaves, various strata of social classes existed within and between the two.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] In examining class relations and the banking system in the South, the economic exploitation of slave labor can be seen to arise from a need to maintain certain conditions for the existence of slavery and from a need for each of the remaining social strata to remain in status quo.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] In order to meet conditions where slavery may continue to exist, members of the master class (e.g., white, landowning, slave-owning) had to compete with other members of the master class to maximize the surplus labor extracted from slaves.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Likewise, in order to remain within the same class, members of the master class (and each subsumed class below) must expand their claim on revenues derived from the slave labor surplus.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Mercantilist ideologies largely explain the rise of the plantation system in the United States.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] In the 16th and 17th centuries under mercantilism, rulers of nations believed that the accumulation of wealth through a favorable balance of trade was the best way to ensure power.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] As a result, several European nations began to colonize the Americas to take advantage of rich natural resources and encourage exports.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] One example of England using its American colonies for economic gain was tobacco.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] When tobacco was first discovered as a recreational substance, there was a widespread social backlash in England, spearheaded by King James I.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] By the middle of the 17th century, however, Parliament had realized the revenue potential of tobacco and quickly changed its official moral stance towards its use.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] As a result, tobacco plantations sprung up across the American South in large numbers to support demand in Europe.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] By 1670, more than half of all tobacco shipped to England was being re-exported to other countries throughout Europe at a premium.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Many claim that being a part of the British mercantilist system was in the best economic interest of the American colonies, as they would not have been able to survive as independent economic entities.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] The plantation system created an environment for the South to experience an economic boom in the 17th, 18th and early 19th centuries.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] However, reliance on both the plantation system and more widespread slave labor, left the South in a precarious economic situation.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] This was the subject of the highly influential 1857 book *The Impending Crisis of the South: How to Meet It*, by Hinton Rowan Helper.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Following the end of the Civil War and into the Reconstruction era (1865–1877), the South experienced economic devastation.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Some states that relied less heavily on the plantation system managed to fare better following its downfall.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] While the South still attracted immigrants from Europe, the North attracted far more during the early-to-mid 1800s, such that by the time of the American Civil War, the population of the North far exceeded the non-enslaved population of the South per the 1860 United States census.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Colin Woodard argued in his 2011 book *American Nations* that the South was relatively less successful in attracting immigrants due to the South's reputation as a more stratified society.
[src:cotton-gin/antebellum-south] Striving immigrants who sought economic advancement thus tended to favor the more egalitarian North, compared to the more aristocratic South, where there were fewer perceived opportunities for advancement.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Archaeological evidence from the region indicate early settlements from the second to first century BCE.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Though the region finds mention in the Hindu epic *Mahabharata*, there is a lack of substantial archaeological evidence regarding its ancient history.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The region is described as one of the frontiers of the Gupta Empire in fourth century CE.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Ahom kingdom was established in the 13th century CE, and ruled till the early 19th century CE.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The period saw various conflicts with the Mughals.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] After the Moamoria rebellion and Burmese invasions weakened the Ahom kingdom, the British started establishing tea estates in the region in the 19th century CE.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The region became part of the Bengal Presidency, and the Assam Province was established in 1912.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Assam Legislative Assembly was formed in 1937.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The province became part of Independent India on 15 August 1947, and was recognised as a state after India became a republic on 26 January 1950.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The state is organised into 35 districts across five divisions.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Assamese and Bodo are the official languages of the state with Meitei recognised as an additional official language in three districts of the Barak Valley and Hojai district, and Bengali in the Barak Valley.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The state is known for its namesake Assam silk and Assam tea, recognised as Geographical Indications in India.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Oil was discovered in the region in 1867, and oil drilling started in 1889.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Wildlife tourism is a major contributor to the economy of the state, aided by the presence of various protected areas including the Kaziranga and Manas National Parks, which are World Heritage Sites.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] More than half of the extant wild population of the one-horned Indian rhinoceros occurs in the state.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The state is a rich biodiversity zone consisting of various ecosystems including tropical rainforests, deciduous forests, riverine grasslands, orchards, and wetlands.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] It receives copious amount of rainfall, which feeds the Brahmaputra River system, whose tributaries and oxbow lakes form a distinctive hydro-geomorphic environment.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The first dated mention of the region comes from *Periplus of the Erythraean Sea* (1st century) and Ptolemy's Geographia (2nd century), which calls the region *Kirrhadia*, apparently after the Kirata population.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In the classical period and up to the 12th century, the region east of the Karatoya River, largely congruent to present-day Assam, was called Kamarupa, and alternatively, Pragjyotisha.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Though a western portion of Assam as a region continued to be called Kamrup, the Ahom kingdom that emerged in the east, and which came to dominate the entire Brahmaputra Valley, was called Assam (e.g.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Mughals used *Asham*); and the British province too was called Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Though the precise etymology of Assam is not clear, the name Assam, first used by the British in the Treaty of Yandabo in 1826, is associated with the Ahom people, originally called *Shyam* (Shan).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Assam and adjoining regions have evidences of human settlement from the beginning of the Stone Age.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The hills at the height of 1,500 to 2,000 feet (460–615 m) were popular habitats probably due to availability of exposed dolerite basalt, useful for tool-making.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Ambari site in Guwahati has revealed Shunga-Kushana era artefacts including flight of stairs and a water tank which may date from 1st century BCE and may be 2,000 years old.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Experts speculate that another significant find at Ambari is Roman era Roman roulette pottery from the 2nd century BCE.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Gupta explains that while Guwahati, formerly known as Pragjyotishpur in ancient times, is mentioned in epics like the Mahabharata and the Puranas, there is a lack of substantial archaeological evidence regarding its ancient history, especially before the 7th century AD.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] According to a late text, Kalika Purana (c.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] 9th–10th century CE), the earliest ruler of Assam was Mahiranga Danava of the Danava dynasty, which was removed by Narakasura of Mithila and established the Bhauma dynasty.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The last of these rulers, also Narakasura, was slain by Krishna.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Naraksura's son Bhagadatta became the king, who (it is mentioned in the Mahabharata) fought for the Kauravas in the battle of Kurukshetra with an army of kiratas, chinas and dwellers of the eastern coast.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] At the same time towards the east in central Assam, Asura kingdom was ruled by another line of kings.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Evidence indicates presence of civilisation in Assam around 2nd century BCE, a rock cut stupa at Sri Surya Pahar has been dated to 200 BCE contemporary with rock cut Karle and Bhaja caves of Maharashtra.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The site is located in a hilly terrain where several rock-cut shivalingas, votive stupas and the deities of Hindu, Buddhist and Jain pantheon are scattered.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Samudragupta's 4th-century-CE Allahabad pillar inscription mentions Kamarupa and Davaka (Central Assam) as frontier kingdoms of the Gupta Empire.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Davaka was later absorbed by Kamarupa, which grew into a large kingdom that spanned from Karatoya River to near present Sadiya and covered the entire Brahmaputra Valley, North Bengal, parts of Bangladesh and, at times Purnea and parts of West Bengal.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The kingdom was ruled by three dynasties who traced their lineage from a mleccha or Kirata Naraka; the Varmanas (c.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] 900–1100 CE), from their capitals in present-day Guwahati (Pragjyotishpura), Tezpur (Haruppeswara) and North Gauhati (Durjaya) respectively.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] All three dynasties claimed descent from Narakasura.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In the reign of the Varman king, Bhaskaravarman (c.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] 600–650 CE), the Chinese traveller Xuanzang visited the region and recorded his travels.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Later, after weakening and disintegration (after the Kamarupa-Palas), the Kamarupa tradition was extended to c.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Medieval Assam history may have started with the advent of Ahoms in the early part of the 13th century and covers their entire rule of 600 years till 1826.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] After the Bengal-Kamata War, the Khen dynasty ended, and Alauddin Hussain Shah issued coins in his name to be "Conqueror of Kamarup and Kamata".
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Chutia, a Bodo-Kachari group by origin, held the regions on both the banks of Brahmaputra with its domain in the area eastwards from Vishwanath (north bank) and Buridihing (south bank), in Upper Assam and in the state of Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] It was annexed by the Ahoms in the year 1524.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The rivalry between the Chutias and Ahoms for the supremacy of eastern Assam led to a series of conflicts between them from the early 16th century.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Dimasa, a Bodo-Kachari dynasty that ruled from the 13th century until 1854, controlled territories stretching from the Dikhow River to central and southern Assam, with their capital at Dimapur.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] By the early 16th century, with the expansion of the Ahom kingdom, the Chutia regions were annexed, and by around 1536, the Kacharis were confined to the areas of Hojai, North Cachar, and parts of Karbi Anglong, later expanding to Cachar.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] At this point, they became more of an ally to the Ahoms than a rival force.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Ahoms, a Tai group, ruled Upper Assam for almost 600 years.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In the year 1228 the Tai-Ahoms came to the Brahmaputra Valley under the leadership of Sukapha along with 9,000 men from Mong Mao, a Tai state, situated in South-Western Yunnan of China, and established his kingdom in Upper Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In 1253, he founded the capital city in a hillock and named it Charaideo.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] At the time of his advent, the area was inhabited by Morans and Borahis.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] To the north and west was the Chutia kingdom, to the south was the Kachari kingdom and to the south-west were the Baro-Bhuyans.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] For the first three centuries, Sukapha and his descendants were primarily focused on administering and consolidating the kingdom.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] During this period, the Ahoms remained largely confined to the southeastern part of Upper Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The reign of Suhungmung marked the first massive expansion of the Ahom kingdom.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Besides sending punitive expeditions against the Nagas, they fought numerous battles with the Chutias, Kacharis, Bhuyans, Turko-Afghans, and the Naras.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In 1522–24 the Chutia kingdom was annexed, and the capital region was placed under the administration of Sadiya-Khowa-Gohain.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] After securing the eastern tract, Suhungmung then expanded his kingdom westwards through conquest and extended it till Marangi to the west of the Dhansiri River.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] When the Kacharis tried to regain the lost territory, they were defeated, and their capital Dimapur was sacked.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Over the remaining part of the Kachari kingdom, a new king Detsung, was placed as a tributary, but Detsung proved disloyal and revolted against the Ahoms.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] A new dependent king was set up on the Kachari throne with the name of Nirbhaynarayan.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Since then, the Kachari kings were regarded as 'thapita sanchita', meaning established and maintained by the Ahom rulers.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Suhungmung's reign also witnessed the first Muslim invasions of the kingdom.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] After a series of battles, the invaders were roundly defeated and were chased up to the Karatoya River.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Sultan of Bengal made peace with the king.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The rising Koch king Biswa Singha also offered his submission, and the Ahom general Ton-Kham granted him all the territories that were received as dowry from the Sultan of Bengal on the condition of annual tribute.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The successors of Suhungmung, Suklenmung and Sukhaamphaa, sent many expeditions against the Bhuyans and Nagas, and there were significant wars with the Koch.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] During the reign of Sukhaamphaa, the Ahoms lost to a Koch army led by Chilarai, and the Ahoms had to accept Koch supremacy and had to give up the tracts north of the Brahmaputra.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] However, the lost tract was soon recovered with further military expeditions.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Soon after the death of Nara Narayan, his kingdom was divided between the sons of Nara Narayan and Chilarai as Koch Hajo and Koch Bihar.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In 1609, Laxmi Narayan, king of Cooch Behar, accepted the vassalage of Mughals, and the Koch Hajo king Raghudev, and later his son Parikshit, sought assistance from the Ahoms.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In 1612, the Mughals attacked Koch Hajo, and his territory up to Barnadi River was annexed into the Mughal domain.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] This brought the Mughals into direct contact with the Ahoms.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Meanwhile, Parikshit was trying to renew his friendship with the Ahoms, but was captured and died on his way to his kingdom.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Later, Balinarayan, a brother of Parikshit who had taken refuge with the Ahoms, was made the king of Darrang in 1615 by the Ahom king Pratap Singha.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] From 1616 onwards, many battles were fought with the Mughal without any tangible result, starting with the Battle of Samdhara.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] After the last battle, the treaty was established in 1639, which fixed the Asurar ali on the south bank and the Barnadi on the north bank of the Brahmaputra as the boundary between the two.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Pratap Singha also enacted the Paik system and created several army and civil administration posts, such as the Borbarua and Borphukan.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Jayadhwaj Singha took advantage of a war of succession between the sons of Shah Jahan, and occupied the imperial territories up to Dhaka.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Aurangzeb, after becoming the emperor, appointed Mir Jumla II, to recover the lost territory.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] After failed negotiations in November 1661, Mir Jumla proceeded with a huge army and fleet to invade the Ahom kingdom.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Ahoms lost at several places, and then captured the Ahom capital Garhgaon.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] During the rainy season, Mir Jumla and his army suffered immeasurable hardship due to the climatic conditions of the valley, in addition to the guerrilla fighting against the invaders.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] After no noticeable gain, negotiation started, and in January 1663, the Treaty of Ghilajharighat was established.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] According to the treaty, the Ahoms acknowledged Mughal supremacy, ceding the territory west of the Bharali on the north bank and the Kalang on the south bank, along with a huge amount of war indemnity, and handing over the sons of the Gohains as hostages, and two Ahom princesses to the Mughal harem.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Soon after the departure of Mir Jumla, Jayadhwaj Singha died, and the new king Chakradhwaj Singha began preparations to overthrow Mughal supremacy and to recover the lost territory.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] After numerous battles, and finally the Battle of Saraighat, the Mughals were forced to retreat.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The period after 1671 was very unstable due to the rivalry among the nobles, who wanted to establish their political power and influence by placing their own choice of prince on the throne.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In 1679, Laluksola Borphukan, in hopes of becoming king with the help of the Mughals, surrendered Guwahati without any battle.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] But after the accession of Gadadhar Singha, at the final Battle of Itakhuli, the Mughals were badly defeated.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The border was then fixed at Manah on the north bank, and the Nagarbera hill on the south bank of the Brahmaputra till its annexation by the East India Company in 1826.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Rudra Singha succeeded Gadadhar Singha, his reign is notable because of his military achievements and his socio-cultural contributions.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] He had both subjugated the Kachari and Jaintia kingdoms, and had captured their kings and forced to accept Ahom suzerainty and agreed for them to pay annual tribute.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Other than that, several expeditions were sent against the **Miris**, the **Daflas**, the Naga Mishmis and the Nagas of Namsung, Dayang and the Rengma Nagas during late 17th century and early 18th century.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Rudra Singha had made extensive preparations for his invasion of Bengal but remained unfulfilled due to his sudden death in 1714.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] After Rudra Singha, the Ahoms achieved no notable military achievements.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] During this period from Siva Singha to Rajeswar Singha, the kingdom witnessed peace and prosperity and was significant for constructive activities and other development.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In the field of religion also, Ekasarana Dharma spread all over the kingdom and started to influence all aspects of people's lives.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The religious heads of the Vaisnavite monastery exerted great influence with royal patronage and established numerous Satras, and most of the people became their disciples.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] So got the Ahom court greatly came under the influence of Sakta Brahman priests and astrologers.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The religious policies concluded by Phuleshwari and the persecutions of unfavored Satras embroiled the situation further, along with the pressure of Paik system in the 18th century.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] This finally resulted in the Moamoria rebellion (1769–1805), which greatly weakened the Ahom kingdom, where the country was greatly depopulated and unorganised.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The political rivalry between the nobles made a pathway for a devastating set of invasions by the Burmese, weakening it more and finally leading to its annexation.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In the later part of the 18th century, religious tensions and atrocities by the nobles led to the Moamoria rebellion (1769–1805), resulting in tremendous casualties of lives and property.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The rebellion was suppressed but the kingdom was severely weakened by the civil war.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Political rivalry between Prime Minister Purnananda Burhagohain and Badan Chandra Borphukan, the Ahom Viceroy of Western Assam, led to an invitation to the Burmese by the latter, in turn leading to three successive Burmese invasions of Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The reigning monarch Chandrakanta Singha tried to check the Burmese invaders but he was defeated after fierce resistance, which led to the Burmese occupation of Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] A reign of terror was unleashed by the Burmese on the Assamese people, who fled to neighbouring kingdoms and British-ruled Bengal.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Burmese reached the East India Company's borders, and the First Anglo-Burmese War ensued in 1824.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The war ended under the Treaty of Yandabo in 1826, with the Company taking control of Western Assam and installing Purandar Singha as king of Upper Assam in 1833.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The arrangement lasted until 1838 and thereafter the British gradually annexed the entire region.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Thereafter the court language and medium of instruction in educational institutions of Assam was made Bengali, instead of Assamese.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Starting from 1836 until 1873, this imposition of a foreign tongue created greater unemployment among the People of Assam and Assamese literature naturally suffered in its growth.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The discovery of *Camellia sinensis* in 1834 in Assam was followed by testing in 1836–37 in London.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The British allowed companies to rent land from 1839 onwards.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Thereafter tea plantations proliferated in Eastern Assam, where the soil and the climate were most suitable.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Problems with the imported Han Chinese labourers from China and hostility from native Assamese resulted in the migration of forced labourers from central and eastern parts of India.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] After initial trial and error with planting the Chinese and the Assamese-Chinese hybrid varieties, the planters later accepted the local *Camellia assamica* as the most suitable variety for Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] By the 1850s, the industry started seeing some profits.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The industry saw initial growth, when in 1861, investors were allowed to own land in Assam and it saw substantial progress with the invention of new technologies and machinery for preparing processed tea during the 1870s.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Despite the commercial success, tea labourers continued to be exploited, working and living under poor conditions.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Fearful of greater government interference, the tea growers formed the Indian Tea Association in 1888 to lobby to retain the status quo.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The organisation was successful in this, but even after India's independence, conditions of the labourers have improved very little.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The *Assam Postage Circle* was established by 1873 under the headship of the Deputy Post Master General.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Initially, Assam was made a part of the Bengal Presidency, then in 1906 it was made a part of Eastern Bengal and Assam province, and in 1912 it was reconstituted into a chief commissioners' province.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In 1913, a legislative council and, in 1937, the Assam Legislative Assembly, were formed in Shillong, the erstwhile capital of the region.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The British tea planters imported labour from central India adding to the demographic canvas.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Assam territory was first separated from Bengal in 1874 as the 'North-East Frontier' non-regulation province, also known as the Assam Chief-Commissionership.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] It was incorporated into the new province of Eastern Bengal and Assam in 1905 after the partition of Bengal (1905–1911) and re-established in 1912 as Assam Province.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, British India consisted of eight provinces that were administered either by a governor or a lieutenant-governor.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Assam Province was one among the major eight provinces of British India.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Bordoloi's major political rival in this time was Sir Saidullah, who was representing the Muslim League, and had the backing of the influential Muslim cleric Maulana Bhasani.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] With the partition of India in 1947, Assam became a constituent state of India.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Sylhet District of Assam (excluding the Karimganj subdivision) was given up to East Pakistan, which later became Bangladesh.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Separatist groups began forming along ethnic lines, and demands for autonomy and sovereignty grew, resulting in the fragmentation of Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In 1961, the government of Assam passed legislation making use of the Assamese language compulsory.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] It was withdrawn later under pressure from Bengali speaking people in Cachar.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The government of India, which has the unilateral powers to change the borders of a state, divided Assam into several states within the borders of what was then Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In 1963, the Naga Hills district became the 16th state of India under the name of Nagaland.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In 1970, in response to the demands of the Khasi, Jaintia and Garo people of the Meghalaya Plateau, the districts containing the Khasi Hills, Jaintia Hills, and Garo Hills were formed into an autonomous state within Assam; in 1972 this became a separate state under the name of Meghalaya.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In 1972, Arunachal Pradesh (the North East Frontier Agency) and Mizoram (from the Mizo Hills in the south) were separated from Assam as union territories; both became states in 1986.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Since the restructuring of Assam after independence, communal tensions and violence remain.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In the 1980s the Brahmaputra Valley saw a six-year Assam Agitation triggered by the discovery of a sudden rise in registered voters on electoral rolls.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The agitation ended after an accord (Assam Accord 1985) between its leaders and the Union Government, which remained unimplemented, causing simmering discontent.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The post 1970s experienced the growth of armed separatist groups such as the United Liberation Front of Asom (ULFA) and the National Democratic Front of Bodoland (NDFB).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In November 1990, the Government of India deployed the Indian army, after which low-intensity military conflicts and political homicides have been continuing for more than a decade.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In recent times, ethnically based militant groups have grown.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Panchayati Raj Act has been applied in Assam, after agitation of the communities due to the sluggish rate of development and general apathy of successive state governments towards Indigenous Assamese communities.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Deadly floods hit the state in 2020 and 2022.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] A significant geographical aspect of Assam is that it contains three of six physiographic divisions of India – The Northern Himalayas (Eastern Hills), The Northern Plains (Brahmaputra plain) and Deccan Plateau (Karbi Anglong).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] As the Brahmaputra flows in Assam the climate here is cold and there is rainfall most of the month.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Geomorphic studies conclude that the Brahmaputra, the life-line of Assam, is an antecedent river older than the Himalayas, which has entrenched itself since they started rising.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The river with steep gorges and rapids in Arunachal Pradesh entering Assam, becomes a braided river (at times 10 mi/16 km wide) and with tributaries, creates a flood plain (Brahmaputra Valley: 50–60 mi/80–100 km wide, 600 mi/1000 km long).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The hills of Karbi Anglong, North Cachar and those in and close to Guwahati (also Khasi-Garo Hills) now eroded and dissected are originally parts of the South Indian Plateau system.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In the south, the Barak River originating in the Barail Range (Assam-Nagaland border) flows through the Cachar district with a 25–30 miles (40–50 km) wide valley and enters Bangladesh with the name Surma River.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Urban centres include Guwahati, one of the 100 fastest growing cities in the world.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Guwahati is also referred to as the "Gateway to North-East India".
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Silchar (in the Barak valley) is the second most populous city in Assam and an important centre of business.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Other large cities include Dibrugarh, an oil and natural gas industry centre.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] With the tropical monsoon climate, Assam is temperate (summer max. at 95–100 °F or 35–38 °C and winter min. at 43–46 °F or 6–8 °C) and experiences heavy rainfall and high humidity.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The climate is characterised by heavy monsoon downpours reducing summer temperatures and affecting foggy nights and mornings in winters, frequent during the afternoons.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Spring (March–April) and autumn (September–October) are usually pleasant with moderate rainfall and temperature.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Assam's agriculture usually depends on the south-west monsoon rains.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Every year, rivers like the Brahmaputra and Barak overflow due to heavy rainfall, causing widespread flooding across Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The rising water levels submerge nearby areas, washing away houses, livestock, and damaging infrastructure such as bridges, railway tracks, and roads, leading to communication breakdowns in many regions.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] This natural disaster also results in numerous fatalities throughout the state.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Assam is one of the richest biodiversity zones in the world and consists of tropical rainforests, deciduous forests, riverine grasslands, bamboo orchards and numerous wetland ecosystems; Many are now protected as national parks and reserved forests.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Assam has wildlife sanctuaries, the most prominent of which are two UNESCO World Heritage Sites-the Kaziranga National Park, on the bank of the Brahmaputra River, and the Manas Wildlife Sanctuary, near the border with Bhutan.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Kaziranga is a refuge for the fast-disappearing Indian one-horned rhinoceros.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Threatened species that are extinct in Assam include the gharial, a critically endangered fish-eating crocodilian, and the pink-headed duck (which may be extinct worldwide).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] For the state bird, the white-winged wood duck, Assam is a globally important area.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In addition to the above, there are three other National Parks in Assam namely Dibru Saikhowa National Park, Nameri National Park and the Orang National Park.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Assam has conserved the one-horned Indian rhinoceros from near extinction, along with the pygmy hog, tiger and numerous species of birds, and it provides one of the last wild habitats for the Asian elephant.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Kaziranga and Manas are both World Heritage Sites.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The state contains Sal tree forests and forest products, much depleted from earlier times.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] A land of high rainfall, Assam displays greenery.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Brahmaputra River tributaries and oxbow lakes provide the region with hydro-geomorphic environment.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The state has the largest population of the wild water buffalo in the world.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The state has the highest diversity of birds in India with around 820 species.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] With subspecies the number is as high as 946.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The mammal diversity in the state is around 190 species.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Assam is remarkably rich in Orchid species and the Foxtail orchid is the state flower of Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The recently established Kaziranga National Orchid and Biodiversity Park boasts more than 500 of the estimated 1,314 orchid species found in India.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Assam has petroleum, natural gas, coal, limestone and other minor minerals such as magnetic quartzite, kaolin, sillimanites, clay and feldspar.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] A small quantity of iron ore is available in western districts.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Discovered in 1867, a USGS estimate shows 399 million barrels (63,400,000 m3) of oil, 1,178 billion cubic feet (3.34×1010 m3) of gas and 67 million barrels (10,700,000 m3) of natural gas liquids in the Assam Geologic Province.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The region is prone to natural disasters like annual floods and frequent mild earthquakes.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Strong earthquakes were recorded in 1869, 1897, and 1950.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The total population of Assam was 26.66 million with 4.91 million households in 2001.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Higher population concentration was recorded in the districts of Kamrup, Nagaon, Sonitpur, Barpeta, Dhubri, Darrang, and Cachar.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Assam's population was estimated at 28.67 million in 2006 and at 30.57 million in 2011 and is expected to reach 34.18 million by 2021 and 35.60 million by 2026.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] As per the 2011 census, the total population of Assam was 31,169,272.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The total population of the state has increased from 26,638,407 to 31,169,272 in the last ten years with a growth rate of 16.93%.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Of the 33 districts, Dhubri, Goalpara, Barpeta, Morigaon, Nagaon, and Hailakandi, recorded growth rates ranging from 20 per cent to 24 per cent during the last decade, whereas Sivasagar and Jorhat, registered around 9 per cent population growth.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] These districts do not have any international border.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In 2011, the literacy rate in the state was 73.18%.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The male literacy rate was 78.81% and the female literacy rate was 67.27%.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In 2001, the census had recorded literacy in Assam at 63.3% with male literacy at 71.3% and female at 54.6%.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The urbanisation rate was recorded at 12.9%.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The growth of population in Assam has increased since the middle decades of the 20th century.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The population grew from 3.29 million in 1901 to 6.70 million in 1941.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The growth in the Western districts and Southern districts was high primarily due to the influx of large number of illegal immigrants from East Pakistan, now Bangladesh.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The mistrust and clashes between indigenous Assamese people and Bengali Muslims started as early as 1952, but is rooted in anti Bengali sentiments of the 1940s.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] At least 77 people died and 400,000 people were displaced in the 2012 Assam violence between indigenous Bodos and Bengali Muslims.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The People of India project has studied 115 of the ethnic groups in Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] 79 (69%) identify themselves regionally, 22 (19%) locally, and 3 trans-nationally.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The earliest settlers were Austroasiatic, Dravidian followed by Tibeto-Burman, Indo-Aryan, and Tai–Kadai people.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Forty-five languages are spoken by different communities, including three major language families: Austroasiatic (5), Sino-Tibetan (24) and Indo-European (12).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Three of the spoken languages do not fall in these families.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] According to the World Air Quality Report 2024 by IQAir, Byrnihat located along the Assam-Meghalaya border is the most polluted city in India.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] According to the 2011 census, 61.47% were Hindus, 34.22% were Muslims.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Christian minorities (3.7%) are found among the Scheduled Tribe and Castes population.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Scheduled Tribe population in Assam is around 13%, of which Bodos account for 40%.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Other religious groups in Assam include Jainism (0.1%), Buddhism (0.2%), Sikhism (0.1%) and Animism (among Khamti, Phake, Aiton etc. communities).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The three popular sects of Hinduism, namely, Shaivisim, Shaktism, and Vaishnavism are prevalent here.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Many Assamese Hindus are also followers of the Ekasarana Dharma sect of Hinduism.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Out of 32 districts of Assam, 9 are Muslim majority according to the 2011 census of India: Dhubri, Goalpara, Barpeta, Morigaon, Nagaon, Karimganj, Hailakandi, Darrang and Bongaigaon.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Assamese and Bodo are the official languages of the state, Meitei (Manipuri) is official in Hojai district and all the three districts of Barak Valley, while Bengali is official in the three districts of Barak Valley, where Sylheti is most commonly spoken.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] According to the language census of 2011 in Assam, out of a total population of around 31 million, Assamese is spoken by more than 22 million total speakers, with more than 15 million people speaking it as their mother tongue and around 7 million as L2 speakers.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Although the number of speakers is growing, the percentage of Assam's population who have it as a mother tongue has fallen slightly.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Assamese serves as *lingua franca* of the region as it is spoken by over 71% of the population (including the one who have listed Assamese as their 2nd language, while 48.38% of them speak it as their mother tongue.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] According to the 24th Edition of Ethnologue: Languages of the World, Assamese is spoken by 15,327,990 persons as mother tongue across the world as of 2021.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] However, 2016 Assam Legislative Assembly election results, have found that 10 million people speaks Assamese as their mother tongue in Assam, which is significantly fewer than the census result of 2011.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The Assamese speakers constituted 48% of the State population according to the 2011 Census.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The various Bengali dialects and closely related languages are spoken by around 9 million people in Assam, and the portion of the population that speaks these languages has grown slightly as per the census.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] In the Brahmaputra Valley, the main Bengali dialect is that of Mymensingh (now in Bangladesh), while in the Barak Valley and Hojai district, Sylheti is the main language which is also considered to be a dialect of Bengali in census.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Bodo is the third most-spoken language followed by Hindi which comes under fourth position.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The population of the Brahmaputra Valley is 27,580,977 according to the 2011 census report.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Assamese is the official language of the Brahmaputra Valley and is spoken by 15 million people comprising 55.65% of the valley population.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The population of the Barak Valley is 3,624,599 according to the 2011 census report.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Bengali is the official as well as the most spoken language of the region with approximately 2,930,378 native speakers.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Although Bengali is reported as the most spoken in the census, the most common spoken language is Sylheti, a language that is generally grouped with Bengali as a dialect.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Meitei (also called Manipuri) is the associate official language of the region with 126,498 speakers.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Hindi, Bishnupriya and Dimasa are the other most widely spoken languages with 362,459, 50,019 and 21,747 native speakers, respectively.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Tripuri, Khasi, Odia, Nepali and Marwari are also spoken by a considerable minority, while 1.84% of the total population speaks other tribal languages.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Traditionally, Assamese was the language of the common folk in the ancient Kamarupa kingdom and in the medieval kingdoms of Dimasa Kachari, Chutiya Kachari, Borahi Kachari, Ahom and Kamata kingdoms.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Traces of the language are found in many poems by Luipa, Sarahapa, and others, in Charyapada (c.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Modern dialects such as Kamrupi and Goalpariya are remnants of this language, which blend into the Rajbanshi and Rangpuri lects spoken in North Bengal which have the same origin.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Moreover, Assamese in its traditional form was used by the ethno-cultural groups in the region as lingua-franca, which spread during the stronger kingdoms and was required for economic integration.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Localised forms of the language still exist in Nagaland and Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Linguistically modern Assamese traces its roots to the version developed by the American Missionaries based on the local form used near Sivasagar (Xiwôxagôr) district.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Assamese (*Ôxômiya*) is a rich language due to its hybrid nature and unique characteristics of pronunciation and softness.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] The presence of Voiceless velar fricative in Assamese makes it a unique among other similar Indo-Aryan languages.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Bodo is spoken largely in Western Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] It is official language of the Bodoland territorial region and co-official language of the state of Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] It is also one of twenty-two languages listed in the Eighth Schedule of the Constitution of India.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Spatial distribution patterns of the ethno-cultural groups, cultural traits and the phenomenon of naming all the major rivers in the North East Region with Bodo-Kachari words (e.g.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Dihing, Dibru, Dihong, D/Tista, and Dikrai) reveal that it was more widely-spoken in ancient times.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] Other languages of Tibeto-Burman origin and related to Bodo-Kachari are Deori, Mising, Karbi, Rabha, and Tiwa.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] There are approximately 590,000 Nepali speakers spread all over the state forming about 1.98% of Assam's total population according to 2011 census.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] There are speakers of Tai languages in Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] A total of six Tai languages were spoken in Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p01] There are also speakers of Dravidian Kurukh and Austroasiatic Khasi speakers scattered across Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Dispur, located in the Guwahati metropolitan region, is the capital of the state.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Dibrugarh was announced as the second capital, and would start functioning in 2027.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Assam has a unicameral legislature consisting of 126 members.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The government is *de jure* headed by the governor and *de facto* led by the Chief Minister of Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The state is divided into five regional divisions, further divided into 35 administrative districts, delineated based on geographic features.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] On 27 June 2016, an island in the Brahmaputra River was bifurcated from the Jorhat district and declared the Majuli district, India's first district that is a river island.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] On 12 January 2021, Bajali was carved out from Barpeta district and formally declared as a district.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] With the announcement made by Governor Jagdish Mukhi, it has become the 34th district of Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] On 31 December 2022, existing four districts Bajali (with Barpeta), Tamulpur(with Udalguri), Biswanath (with Sonitpur) and Hojai(with Nagaon) and number of district came down to 31.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] However, after the delimitation exercise was carried out in Assam, the Assam Cabinet reconstituted the 4 new districts (Bajali, Tamulpur, Biswanath and Hojai), taking the number of districts to 35 again.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The administrative districts are further subdivided into 54 "Subdivisions" or *Mahakuma*.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Every district is administered from a district headquarters with the office of the Deputy Commissioner, District Magistrate, Office of the District Panchayat and usually with a district court.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The local governance system is organised under the *jila-parishad* (District Panchayat) for a district, *panchayat* for group of or individual rural areas and under the urban local bodies for the towns and cities.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] There are now 2489 village panchayats covering 26247 villages in Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The 'town-committee' or *nagar-somiti* for small towns, 'municipal board' or *pouro-sobha* for medium towns and municipal corporation or *pouro-nigom* for the cities consist of the urban local bodies.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] For revenue purposes, the districts are divided into revenue circles and *mouza*s; for the development projects, the districts are divided into 219 'development-blocks' and for law and order these are divided into 206 police stations or *thana*.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Guwahati is the largest metropolitan area and urban conglomeration administered under the highest form of urban local body – Guwahati Municipal Corporation in Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The Corporation administers an area of 216.79 km2 (83.70 sq mi).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Apart from Guwahati Municipal Corporation and Dibrugarh Municipal Corporation All other urban centres are managed under Municipal Boards.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Establishment of Guwahati Municipal Corporation.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Dibrugarh, the second township of Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Formation of Goalpara Municipality, 1875.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Formation of Golaghat Municipality, 1920.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Formation of Silchar Municipality, 1922.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The state has three autonomous councils under the sixth schedule of the Indian Constitution.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] In March 2024, the Assam cabinet had given green signal for 'Kiran Sheikh' development council for the 'Kiran Sheikh' community in Barak Valley.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The state was ruled by Indian National Congress led governments since its inception in 1950 till 2016.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] On 19 May 2016, the Bharatiya Janata Party under the leadership of Sarbananda Sonowal won the assembly elections, thus forming the first BJP-led government in Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The BJP government was re-elected in 2021 under the leadership of Himanta Biswa Sarma.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] According to Assam Government, Assam has border dispute with four states namely Meghalaya, Mizoram, Nagaland, Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Mizoram used to be a district of Assam as Lushai hills before being carved out as a separate union territory and later, becoming another state in 1987.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Because of the history, the district's borders did not really matter for locals for a long time.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Mizoram shares a border with the districts Cachar, Hailakandi and Karimganj which comes under Barak valley region of Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Over time, the two states started having different perceptions about where the demarcation should be.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] While Mizoram wants it to be along an Inner Line Permit notified in 1875 to protect tribals from outside influence, which Mizos feel is part of their historical homeland, Assam wants it to be demarcated according to district boundaries drawn up much later.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Meghalaya has identified close to a dozen areas on which it has a dispute with Assam about the state's borders.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The chief ministers of the two states, Himanta Biswa Sarma and Megahalya's Conrad Sangma, recently held the first-ever meeting on inter-state border dispute.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Both the states have agreed to individually assess the claims for all 12 areas flagged by Meghalaya in the past.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] A second round of discussion between the two state CMs will be held next month of August.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The border dispute between the two states has been going on since the formation of Nagaland in 1963.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The two states lay claim to Merapani, a small village next to the plains of Assam's Golaghat district.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] There have been reports of violent clashes in the region since the 1960s.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Assam shares an 804.10 km inter-state boundary with Arunachal Pradesh.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The state of Arunachal Pradesh, created in 1987, claims some land that traditionally belonged to its residents has been given to Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] A tripartite committee had recommended that certain territories be transferred from Assam to Arunachal.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The two states have since been battling it out in the Supreme court of India over the issue.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Some incidents of local violence have been reported from the borders.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Upper Assam's various Tai-Ahom organisations like "Ahom Tai Mangoliya Rajya Parishad" (ATMRP), has been demanding a separate Ahomland state since 1967, comprising erstwhile Un-divided Sivasagar and Lakhimpur districts (today's Upper Assam and North Assam divisions) respectively.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] On 2023, "Tai Ahom Yuba Parishad, Assam" (TAYPA) have organised a protest at Chachal and have demanded separate Ahomland state.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The Barak Valley of Assam comprising the present districts of Cachar, Karimganj and Hailakandi is contiguous to Sylhet (Bengal plains), where the Bengalis, according to historian J.B.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Bhattacharjee, had settled well before the colonial period, influencing the culture of Dimasa Kacaharis.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Bhattacharjee describes that the Dimasa kings spoke Bengali, the inscriptions and coins were written in Bengali script and the official language of the court was also Bengali.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Migrations to Cachar increased after the British annexation of the region.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Silchar is the proposed capital of Barak state.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The agitation for the creation of a separate Bodoland state resulted in an agreement between the Indian Government, the Assam state government and the Bodo Liberation Tigers Force.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] According to the agreement made on 10 February 2003, the Bodoland Territorial Council, an entity subordinate to the government of Assam, was created to govern four districts covering 3082 Bodo Kachari-majority villages in Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Elections to the council were held on 13 May 2003, and Hagrama Mohilary was sworn in as the chief of the 46-member council on 4 June.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The Dimasa people of northeast India have been demanding a separate state called Dimaraji or "Dimaland" for several decades.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] It would comprise the Dimasa-Kachari inhabited areas, namely Dima Hasao district, Cachar district, parts of Barak Valley, Nagaon district, Hojai district and Karbi Anglong district in Assam together with part of Dimapur district in Nagaland.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Karbi Anglong is one of the 35 districts of Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Karbi Anglong was previously known as Mikir Hills.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] It was part of the Excluded Areas and Partially Excluded Areas (the present North East India) in British India.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The British Indian government had never included this area under their government's jurisdiction.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Thereby, no government development work or activity were done, nor any tax levied from the hills including Karbi Anglong.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The first memorandum for a Karbi homeland was presented to Governor Reid on 28 October 1940 by Semsonsing Ingti and Khorsing Terang at Mohongdijua.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The Karbi leaders were then, a part of the All Party Hill Leaders' Conference (APHLC) which was formed on 6 July 1960.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The movement again gained momentum when the Karbi Anglong District Council passed a resolution demanding a Separate State in 1981.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Then again from 1986 through the leadership of Autonomous State Demand Committee (ASDC), demanded Autonomous statehood of Karbi Anglong and Dima Hasao under Article 244(A).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] In 2002, the Karbi Anglong Autonomous Council passed another resolution to press for the demand of statehood.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Several other memoranda were submitted at different times by several organisations.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The demand for a separate state turned violent on 31 July 2013 when student demonstrators set government buildings on fire.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Following the incident, the elected leaders of Karbi Anglong jointly submitted a memorandum to the Prime Minister of India demanding a separate State.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Demographic wise, more than half of the Karbi Anglong population is made up of Indigenous Karbi tribe with significant migrants from other parts of India.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] After the 1964 East Pakistan riots many Bengali Hindus have poured into Assam as refugees and the number of Hindu migrants in the state rose to 1,068,455 in 1968 (sharply after 4 years of the riot).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The fourth patches numbering around 347,555 have just arrived after Bangladesh liberation war of 1971 as refugees and most of them being Bengali speaking Hindus have decided to stay back in Assam permanently afterwards.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Though the governments of India and Bangladesh made agreements for the repatriation of certain groups of refugees after the second and third waves, a large presence of refugees and other migrants and their descendants remained in the state.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Nevertheless, still people of Bangladesh have been immigrating to Assam on regular basis.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] As per reports, about 635 of Bangladeshi people mostly Hindus, use to immigrate to Assam daily.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Besides migration caused by displacement, there is also a large and continual unregulated movement between Assam and neighbouring regions of Bangladesh with an exceptionally porous border.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The situation is called a risk to Assam's as well as India's security.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The continual illegal entry of people into Assam, mostly from Bangladesh, has caused economic upheaval and social and political unrest.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] During the Assam Movement (1979–1985), the All Assam Students Union (AASU) and others demanded that government stop the influx of immigrants and deport those who had already settled.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] During this period, 855 people (the AASU says 860) died in various conflicts with migrants and police.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] In 1985, the Indian Government and leaders of the agitation signed the Assam accord to settle the conflict.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The 1991 census made the changing demographics of border districts more visible.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Since 2010, the Indian Government has undertaken the updating of the National Register of Citizens for Assam, and in 2018 the 32.2 million residents of Assam were subject to a review of their citizenship.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] In January 2019, the Assam's peasant organisation Krishak Mukti Sangram Samiti (KMSS) claimed that there are around 20 lakh Hindu Bangladeshis in Assam who would become Indian citizens if the Citizenship (Amendment) Bill is passed.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] BJP, however claimed that only eight lakh Hindu Bangladeshis will get citizenship.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] According to various sources, the total number of illegal Hindu Bangladeshis is hard to ascertain.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] According to the census data, the number of Hindu immigrants have been largely exaggerated.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] In February 2020, the Assam Minority Development Board announced plans to segregate illegal Bangladeshi Muslim immigrants from the indigenous Muslims of the state, though some have expressed problems in identifying an indigenous Muslim person.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] According to the board, there are 1.4 crore Muslims in the state, of which 1 crore are of Bangladeshi origin.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] A report reveals that out of total 33 districts in Assam, Bangladeshis dominate almost 15 districts of Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] In the rainy season every year, the Brahmaputra and other rivers overflow their banks and flood adjacent land.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Flood waters wash away property including houses and livestock.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Damage to crops and fields harms the agricultural sector.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Bridges, railway tracks, and roads are also damaged, harming transportation and communication, and in some years requiring food to be air-dropped to isolated towns.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Some deaths are attributed to the floods.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Unemployment is a chronic problem in Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] It is variously blamed on poor infrastructure, limited connectivity, and government policy; on a "poor work culture"; on failure to advertise vacancies; and on government hiring candidates from outside Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] In 2020 a series of violent lynchings occurred in the region.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Assam has 12 medical colleges at present with 4 more scheduled to be completed by 2026–27.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Assam's economy is based on agriculture and oil.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Assam produces more than half of India's tea.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The Assam-Arakan basin holds about a quarter of the country's oil reserves, and produces about 12% of its total petroleum.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] According to the recent estimates, Assam's per capita GDP is ₹6,157 at constant prices (1993–94) and ₹10,198 at current prices; almost 40% lower than that in India.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] According to the recent estimates, per capita income in Assam has reached ₹6756 (1993–94 constant prices) in 2004–05, which is still much lower than India's.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Between 1951 and 1979, Assam registered an average level of real gross domestic product growth compared to the national average.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] However, the state's real gdp growth lagged behind the national average after 1979 due to socio-political instability.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Between 1981 and 2001, Assam's GSDP increased 3.3 per cent annually compared to the national average of 6 per cent.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Since the 2000s, Assam has registered higher levels of real gross domestic product growth.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] GSDP at constant (1999-2000) prices increased 5.33 per cent annually between 2002 and 2007.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Real GSDP increased 6.78 per cent annually between 2007 and 2012.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Real GSDP at constant (2011-12) prices increased approximately 7.6 per cent annually between 2012 and 2016.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Real GSDP at constant (2011-12) prices increased approximately 7.0 per cent annually between 2016 and 2025.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Unemployment is one of the major problems in Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] This problem can be attributed to overpopulation and a faulty education system.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Every year, large numbers of students obtain higher academic degrees but because of non-availability of proportional vacancies, most of these students remain unemployed.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] A number of employers hire over-qualified or efficient, but under-certified, candidates, or candidates with narrowly defined qualifications.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The problem is exacerbated by the growth in the number of technical institutes in Assam which increases the unemployed community of the State.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The reluctance on the part of the departments concerned to advertise vacancies in vernacular language has also made matters worse for local unemployed youths particularly for the job-seekers of Grade C and D vacancies.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Reduction of the unemployed has been threatened by illegal immigration from Bangladesh.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] This has increased the workforce without a commensurate increase in jobs.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Immigrants compete with local workers for jobs at lower wages, particularly in construction, domestics, Rickshaw-pullers, and vegetable sellers.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The government has been identifying (via NRC) and deporting illegal immigrants.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Continued immigration is exceeding deportation.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] In Assam among all the productive sectors, agriculture makes the highest contribution to its domestic sectors, accounting for more than a third of Assam's income and employs 69% of workforce.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Assam's biggest contribution to the world is Assam tea.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] It has its own variety, *Camellia sinensis* var.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The state produces rice, rapeseed, mustard seed, jute, potato, sweet potato, banana, papaya, areca nut, sugarcane and turmeric.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Assam's agriculture is yet to experience modernisation in a real sense.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] With implications for food security, per capita food grain production has declined in the past five decades.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Productivity has increased marginally, but is still low compared to highly productive regions.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] For instance, the yield of rice (a staple food of Assam) was just 1531 kg per hectare against India's 1927 kg per hectare in 2000–01 (which itself is much lower than Egypt's 9283, US's 7279, South Korea's 6838, Japan's 6635 and China's 6131 kg per hectare in 2001).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] On the other hand, after having strong domestic demand, and with 1.5 million hectares of inland water bodies, numerous rivers and 165 varieties of fishes, fishing is still in its traditional form and production is not self-sufficient.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Floods in Assam greatly affect the farmers and the families dependent on agriculture because of large-scale damage of agricultural fields and crops by flood water.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Every year, flooding from the Brahmaputra and other rivers deluges places in Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The water levels of the rivers rise because of rainfall resulting in the rivers overflowing their banks and engulfing nearby areas.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Apart from houses and livestock being washed away by flood water, bridges, railway tracks and roads are also damaged by the calamity, which causes communication breakdown in many places.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Fatalities are also caused by the natural disaster in many places of the state.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] On 30 August 2023, Maligaon Flyover was inaugurated.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The flyover is Assam's longest flyover, spanning 2.63 kilometres and connecting Maligaon Chariali to Kamakhya Gate in Guwahati.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Handlooms and handicrafts are traditional industries that continue to survive, especially among rural women, in the state.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Assam's proximity to some neighbouring countries such as Bangladesh, Nepal and Bhutan, benefits its trade.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The major Border checkpoints through which border trade flows to Bangladesh from Assam are : Sutarkandi (Karimganj), Dhubri, Mankachar (Dhubri) and Golokanj.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] To facilitate border trade with Bangladesh, Border Trade Centres have been developed at Sutarkandi and Mankachar.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] It has been proposed in the 11th five-year plan to set up two more Border Trade Center, one at Ledo connecting China and other at Darrang connecting Bhutan.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] There are several Land Custom Stations (LCS) in the state bordering Bangladesh and Bhutan to facilitate border trade.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The Lokpriya Gopinath Bordoloi International Airport at Guwahati, with international flights to Bangkok and Singapore offered by Druk Air of Bhutan, was the 12th busiest airport of India in 2012.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] The cities of Guwahati in the west and Dibrugarh in the east with good rail, road and air connectivity are the two important nerve centres of Assam, to be selected by Asian Development Bank for providing $200 million for improvement of urban infrastructure.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Assam is a producer of crude oil and it accounts for about 15% of India's crude output, exploited by the Assam Oil Company Ltd., and natural gas in India.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Oil was discovered in Makum in 1867, and oil drilling started in 1889.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Most of the oilfields are located in the Eastern Assam region.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Assam has four oil refineries in Digboi (Asia's first and world's second refinery), Guwahati, Bongaigaon and Numaligarh and with a total capacity of 7 million metric tonnes (7.7 million short tons) per annum.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Asia's first refinery was set up at Digboi and discoverer of Digboi oilfield was the Assam Railways & Trading Company Limited (AR&T Co.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Ltd.), a registered company of London in 1881.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] One of the biggest public sector oil company of the country Oil India Ltd. has its plant and headquarters at Duliajan.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] There are several other industries, including a chemical fertiliser plant at Namrup, petrochemical industries in Namrup and Bongaigaon, paper mills at Jagiroad, Hindustan Paper Corporation Ltd.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Township Area Panchgram and Jogighopa, sugar mills in Barua Bamun Gaon, Chargola, Kampur, cement plants in Bokajan and Badarpur, and a cosmetics plant of Hindustan Unilever (HUL) at Doom Dooma.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Moreover, there are other industries such as jute mill, textile and yarn mills, Assam silk, and silk mills.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Many of these industries are facing losses and closure due to lack of infrastructure and improper management practices.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p02] Wildlife, cultural, and historical destinations have attracted visitors.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Assamese Culture is described as hybrid and syncretic in nature due to the assimilation of numerous ethnic groups and cultural practices of Austroasiatic, Tibeto-Burman, Indo-Aryan and Tai inhabitants.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Therefore, both local elements or the local elements in Sanskritised forms are distinctly found.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] The modern culture has been influenced by events in the British and the post-British era.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Assamese language was standardised by American Baptist Missionaries such as Nathan Brown, Dr.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Miles Bronson and local pundits such as Hemchandra Barua with the dialect spoken in undivided Sibsagar district (the centre of the Ahom kingdom) forming the standardised dialect.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Increasing efforts of standardisation in the 20th century alienated the localised forms present in different areas and with the less-assimilated ethno-cultural groups (many source-cultures).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] However, Assamese culture in its hybrid form and nature is one of the richest, still developing and in true sense is a 'cultural system' with sub-systems.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Many source-cultures of the Assamese cultural-system are still surviving either as sub-systems or as sister entities, e.g. the; Bodo or Karbi or Mishing.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] It is important to keep the broader system closer to its roots and at the same time focus on development of the sub-systems.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Some of the common and unique cultural traits in the region are peoples' respect towards areca-nut and betel leaves, symbolic (gamosa, arnai, etc.), traditional silk garments (e.g. mekhela chador, traditional dress of Assamese women) and towards forefathers and elderly.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Moreover, great hospitality and bamboo culture are common.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Symbolism is an ancient cultural practice in Assam and is still a very important part of the Assamese way of life.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Various elements are used to represent beliefs, feelings, pride, identity, etc.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] There were many other symbolic elements and designs, but are now only found in literature, art, sculpture, architecture, etc. or in use today for only religious purposes.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] The typical designs of *Assamese-lion*, *dragon* (ngi-ngao-kham), and *flying-lion* (Naam-singho) are used for symbolising various purposes and occasions.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] The archaeological sites such as the Madan Kamdev (c.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] 9th–10th centuries CE) exhibits mass-scale use of lions, dragon-lions and many other figures of demons to show case power and prosperity.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] The Vaishnavite monasteries (Sattras) and many other architectural sites of the late medieval period display the use of lions and dragons for symbolic effects.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] There are diversified important traditional festivals in Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Bihu is the most important festival of Assam and is celebrated all over the state.The Assamese new year (Ek Bohag) is celebrated in April of the Gregorian calendar.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Moreover, there are other important traditional festivals being celebrated every year on different occasions at different places.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Many of these are celebrated by different ethno-cultural groups (sub and sister cultures).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Christmas is observed with great merriment by Christians of various denominations, including Catholics, Protestants and Baptists, throughout Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Durga Puja is widely celebrated across the state.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Muslims celebrate two Eids (Eid ul-Fitr and Eid al-Adha) with much eagerness all over Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Other few yearly celebrations are Brahmaputra Beach Festival, Guwahati, Kaziranga Elephant Festival, Kaziranga and Dehing Patkai Festival, Lekhapani, Karbi Youth Festival of Diphu and International Jatinga Festival, Jatinga can not be forgotten.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Few yearly *Mela's* like Jonbeel Mela, started in the 15th century by the Ahom Kings, Ambubachi Mela, Guwahati etc.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Asom Divas or Sukapha Divas (2 December) is celebrated to commemorate the advent of the first king of the Ahom kingdom in Assam after his journey over the Patkai Hills.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Lachit Divas (24 November) is celebrated on the birth anniversary of the great Ahom general Lachit Borphukan.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Sarbananda Sonowal, the chief minister of Assam took part in the Lachit Divas celebration at the statue of Lachit Borphukan at Brahmaputra riverfront on 24 November 2017.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] He said, the first countrywide celebration of 'Lachit Divas' would take place in New Delhi followed by state capitals such as Hyderabad, Bangalore and Kolkata in a phased manner.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Performing arts include: *Ankia Naat* (*Onkeeya Naat*), a traditional Vaishnav dance-drama (*Bhaona*) popular since the 15th century CE.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] It makes use of large masks of gods, goddesses, demons and animals and in between the plays a *Sutradhar* (*Xutrodhar*) continues to narrate the story.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] *Sattriya* (*Sotriya*) dance related to Vaishnav tradition is a classical form of dance.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Moreover, there are several other age-old dance-forms such as Barpeta's *Bhortal Nritya*, Deodhani Nritya, *Ojapali*, *Beula Dance*, *Ka Shad Inglong Kardom*, *Nimso Kerung*, etc.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] The tradition of modern moving theatres is typical of Assam with immense popularity of many Mobile theatre groups such as Kohinoor, Brindabon, etc..
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Among the new generation, Zubeen Garg, Angaraag Mahanta and Joi Barua.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] There is an award given in the honour of Bishnu Prasad Rabha for achievements in the cultural/music world of Assam by the state government.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Contemporary Assamese music also saw the rise of Zubeen Garg, one of the most popular modern singers of the region.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] His Assamese song "Mayabini Raatir Bukut" has achieved iconic status and is widely regarded as an anthem in Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Typically, an Assamese meal consists of many things such as *bhat* (rice) with *dayl/ daly* (lentils), *masor jool* (fish stew), *mangxô* (meat stew) and stir fried greens or herbs and vegetables.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] The two main characteristics of a traditional meal in Assam are *khar* (an Alkali, named after its main ingredient) and *tenga* (preparations bearing a characteristically rich and tangy flavour).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] *Khorika* is the smoked or fire grilled meat eaten with meals.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Pitika (mash) is another delicacy of Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] It includes alu pitika (mashed potatoes), bilahi (tomatoes), bengena (brinjals) or even masor pitika (fish).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Commonly consumed varieties of meat include Mutton, fowl, duck/goose, fish, pigeon, pork and beef (among Muslim and Christian indigenous Assamese ethnic groups).
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Grasshoppers, locusts, silkworms, snails, eels, bat wild fowl, squab and other birds, and venison are also eaten, albeit in moderation.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] A variety of different rice cultivars are grown and consumed in different ways, viz., roasted, ground, boiled or just soaked.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Fish curries made of free range wild fish as well as *Bôralí*, *rôu*, *illish*, or *sitôl* are the most popular.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Another favourite combination is *luchi* (fried flatbread), a curry which can be vegetarian or non-vegetarian.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Many indigenous Assamese communities households still continue to brew their traditional alcoholic beverages; examples include: Laupani, Xaaj, Paniyo, Jou, Joumai, Hor, Apong, Sujen etc.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Such beverages are served during traditional festivities.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Declining them is considered socially offensive.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Assamese food is generally served in traditional bell metal dishes and platters like *Kanhi*, *Maihang* and so on.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Assamese literature dates back to the composition of Charyapada, and later on works like Saptakanda Ramayana by Madhava Kandali, which is the first translation of the Ramayana into an Indo-Aryan language, contributed to Assamese literature.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Sankardeva's Borgeet, Ankia Naat, Bhaona and Satra tradition backed the 15th-16th century Assamese literature.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Written during the Reign of Ahoms, the Buranjis are notable literary works which are prominently historical manuscripts.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Most literary works are written in Assamese although other local language such as Bodo and Dimasa are also represented.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] In the 19th and 20th century, Assamese and other literature was modernised by authors including Lakshminath Bezbaroa, Birinchi Kumar Barua, Hem Barua, Dr.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Mamoni Raisom Goswami, Bhabendra Nath Saikia, Birendra Kumar Bhattacharya, Hiren Bhattacharyya, Homen Borgohain, Bhabananda Deka, Rebati Mohan Dutta Choudhury, Mahim Bora, Lil Bahadur Chettri, Syed Abdul Malik, Surendranath Medhi, Hiren Gohain etc.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] The archaic Mauryan Stupas discovered in and around Goalpara district are the earliest examples (c.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] 100 CE) of ancient art and architectural works.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] The remains discovered in Daparvatiya (*Doporboteeya*) archaeological site with a beautiful doorframe in Tezpur are identified as the best examples of artwork in ancient Assam with influence of Sarnath School of Art of the late Gupta period.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Painting is an ancient tradition of Assam.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Xuanzang (7th century CE) mentions that among the Kamarupa king Bhaskaravarma's gifts to Harshavardhana there were paintings and painted objects, some of which were on Assamese silk.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Many of the manuscripts such as Hastividyarnava (A Treatise on Elephants), the *Chitra Bhagawata* and in the Gita Govinda from the Middle Ages bear excellent examples of traditional paintings.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Assam has a rich tradition of crafts, Cane and bamboo craft, bell metal and brass craft, silk and cotton weaving, toy and mask making, pottery and terracotta work, wood craft, jewellery making, and musical instruments making have remained as major traditions.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Cane and bamboo craft provide the most commonly used utilities in daily life, ranging from household utilities, weaving accessories, fishing accessories, furniture, musical instruments, construction materials, etc.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Utilities and symbolic articles such as *Sorai* and *Bota* made from bell metal and brass are found in every Assamese household.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Hajo and Sarthebari (*Sorthebaary*) are the most important centres of traditional bell-metal and brass crafts.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Assam is the home of several types of silks, the most prestigious are: Muga – the natural golden silk, Pat – a creamy-bright-silver coloured silk and Eri – a variety used for manufacturing warm clothes for winter.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Apart from Sualkuchi (*Xualkuchi*), the centre for the traditional silk industry, in almost every parts of the Brahmaputra Valley, rural households produce silk and silk garments with excellent embroidery designs.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Moreover, various ethno-cultural groups in Assam make different types of cotton garments with unique embroidery designs and wonderful colour combinations.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Moreover, Assam possesses unique crafts of toy and mask making mostly concentrated in the Vaishnav Monasteries, pottery and terracotta work in western Assam districts and wood craft, iron craft, jewellery, etc. in many places across the region.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Print media include Assamese dailies *Amar Asom*, *Asomiya Khabar*, *Asomiya Pratidin*, *Dainik Agradoot*, *Dainik Janambhumi*, *Dainik Asam*, *Gana Adhikar*, *Janasadharan* and *Niyomiya Barta*.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] *Asom Bani*, *Sadin* and *Janambhumi* are Assamese weekly newspapers.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] The English dailies of Assam include *The Assam Tribune*, *The Sentinel*, *The Telegraph*, *The Times of India*, *The North East Times*, *Eastern Chronicle* and *The Hills Times*.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] *Thekar*, in the Karbi language has the largest circulation of any daily from Karbi Anglong district.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] *Bodosa* has the highest circulation of any Bodo daily from BTR.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] *Dainik Jugasankha* is a Bengali daily with editions from Dibrugarh, Guwahati, Silchar and Kolkata.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] *Dainik Samayik Prasanga*, *Dainik Prantojyoti*, *Dainik Janakantha* and *Nababarta Prasanga* are other prominent Bengali dailies published in the Barak Valley towns of Karimganj and Silchar.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Hindi dailies include *Purvanchal Prahari*, *Pratah Khabar* and *Dainik Purvoday*.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Broadcasting stations of All India Radio have been established in 22 cities across the state.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Local news and music are the main priority for those stations.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Assam has three public service broadcasting service stations of state-owned Doordarshan at Dibrugarh, Guwahati and Silchar.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] The Guwahati-based satellite news channels include Assam Talks, DY 365, News Live, News18 Assam North East, North East Live, Prag News and Pratidin Time.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Boka Chaul was awarded the Geographical Indication (GI) status tag from the Geographical Indications Registry, under the Union Government of India, on 30 July 2018 and is valid until 24 July 2026.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] Lotus Progressive Centre (LPC) and Centre for Environment Education (CEE) from Guwahati, proposed the GI registration of Boka Chaul.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] After filing the application in July 2018, the rice was granted the GI tag in 2023 by the Geographical Indication Registry in Chennai, making the name "Boka Chaul" exclusive to the rice grown in the region.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] It thus became the second rice variety from Assam after Joha rice and the 7th type of goods from Assam to earn the GI tag.
[src:cotton-gin/assam-p03] The GI tag protects the rice from illegal selling and marketing, and gives it legal protection and a unique identity.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] A **screw conveyor** or **auger conveyor** is a mechanism that uses a rotating helical screw blade, called a "*flighting*", usually within a tube, to move liquid or granular materials.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] They are used in many bulk handling industries.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Screw conveyors in modern industry are often used horizontally or at a slight incline as an efficient way to move semi-solid materials, including food waste, wood chips, aggregates, cereal grains, animal feed, boiler ash, meat, bone meal, municipal solid waste, and many others.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] The first type of screw conveyor was the Archimedes' screw, used since ancient times to pump irrigation water.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] They usually consist of a trough or tube containing either a spiral blade coiled around a shaft, driven at one end and held at the other, or a "*shaftless spiral*", driven at one end and free at the other.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] The rate of volume transfer is proportional to the rotation rate of the shaft.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] In industrial control applications, the device is often used as a variable rate feeder by varying the rotation rate of the shaft to deliver a measured rate or quantity of material into a process.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Screw conveyors can be operated with the flow of material inclined upward.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] When space allows, this is a very economical method of elevating and conveying.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] As the angle of inclination increases, the capacity of a given unit rapidly decreases.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] The rotating part of the conveyor is sometimes called simply an auger.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] The "grain auger" is used in agriculture to move grain from trucks, grain carts, or grain trailers into grain storage bins (from where it is later removed by gravity chutes at the bottom).
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] A grain auger may be powered by an electric motor; a tractor, through the power take-off; or sometimes an internal combustion engine mounted on the auger.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] The helical rotates inside a long metal tube, moving the grain upwards.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] On the lower end, a hopper receives grain from the truck or grain cart.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] A chute on the upper end guides the grain into the destination location.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] The modern grain auger of today's farming communities was invented by Peter Pakosh.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] His grain mover employed a screw-type auger with a minimum of moving parts, a totally new application for this specific use.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Pakosh, however, went on to design and build a first prototype auger in 1945, and 8 years later start selling tens of thousands under the 'Versatile' name, making it the standard for modern grain augers.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] A specialized form of grain auger is used to transfer grain into a seed drill and is usually quite a lot smaller in both length and diameter than the augers used to transfer grain to or from a truck, grain cart or bin.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] This type of auger is known as a "drill fill".
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Grain augers with a small diameter, regardless of the use they are put to, are often called "pencil augers".
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Centerless augers are particularly popular in industrial animal farming facilities, where the primary application is distributing animal feed from a central storage location to individual or group feeding devices.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] The flexible nature of the auger wire allows feed or other materials to change elevation and move at angles.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] The first centerless auger was patented by Eldon Hostetler and Chore-Time Equipment in the context of this application.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Various other applications of the screw or auger conveyor include its use in snowblowers, to move snow towards an impeller, where it is thrown into the discharge chute.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Combine harvesters use both enclosed and open augers to move the unthreshed crop into the threshing mechanism and to move the grain into and out of the machine's hopper.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Ice resurfacers use augers to remove loose ice particles from the surface of the ice.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] An auger is also a central component of an injection molding machine.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] An auger is used in some rubbish compactors to push the rubbish into a lowered plate at one end for compaction.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Augers are also present in food processing.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] They are a tool of choice in powder processing when it comes to conveyor does precisely bulk solids (powders, pellets...).
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] In a conventional meat grinder, chunks of meat are led by the auger through a spinning blade and a holed plate.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] This method emulsifies the fat in beef to soften hamburger patties and is also used to produce a wide variety of sausages and loaves.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Augers are also used to force food products through dies to produce pellets.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] These are then processed further to produce products such as bran flakes.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Augers are also used in oil fields as a method of transporting rock cuttings away from the shakers to skips.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Augers are also used in some types of pellet stoves and barbecue grills, to move fuel from a storage hopper into the firebox in a controlled manner.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Augers are often used in machining, wherein the machine tools may include an auger to direct the swarf (scrap metal or plastic) away from the workpiece.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Screw conveyors can also be found in wastewater treatment plants to evacuate solid waste from the treatment process.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] The amphibious infantry fighting vehicle BMP-3 uses an auger-type propulsion unit in water.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] The Olds elevator is a variant of a screw conveyor developed by Australian engineer Peter Olds in 2002.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Rather than rotate a central screw blade, a stationary screw is contained within a rotating casing that scoops surrounding material into its base.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Following similar principles to the conventional screw conveyor, the Olds elevator can lift bulk materials efficiently.
[src:cotton-gin/auger-conveyor] Since its invention, it has been assessed as a viable system for industrial uses by a number of academics.
[src:cotton-gin/buddhist] Buddhists are broadly classified into two main categories: Bhikkhus and Bhikkhunīs, who are ordained monastics and serve as religious teachers, and Upāsakas and Upāsikās, who are lay followers living a household life while supporting and practicing the teachings of Buddhism.
[src:cotton-gin/buddhist] In ancient India, followers of the Buddha were sometimes identified as Shakyas, after the clan into which the Buddha was born.
[src:cotton-gin/buddhist] The English word *Buddhist* emerged in the early 19th century, formed from "Buddha" and the suffix "-ist", denoting an adherent of a belief system; its earliest recorded usage in English dates to 1810.
[src:cotton-gin/buddhist] Buddhism comprises numerous schools and traditions, alongside non-denominational and secular forms.
[src:cotton-gin/buddhist] The two largest traditions are Theravāda Buddhism, predominant in Sri Lanka, Thailand, Myanmar, Cambodia, and Laos, and Mahayana Buddhism, which is dominant in China, Japan, Korea, and Vietnam.
[src:cotton-gin/buddhist] There are approximately 320 million Buddhists worldwide, accounting for about 4% of the global population.
[src:cotton-gin/buddhist] Buddhism has declined in the recent years due to lower fragility rates and rising irreligion in East Asia.
